u00e9r\u00f4me E.|chapter=A Global Movement for Real Democracy? The Resonance of Anti-Austerity Protest from Spain and Greece to Occupy Wall Street.|title= Street Politics in the Age of Austerity|pages=227\u2013250 |editor1=Marcos Ancelovici|editor2= Pascale Dufour|editor3= H\u00e9lo\u00efse Nez|chapter-url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/311717832|publisher=Amsterdam University Press|year=2016|doi=10.1515/9789048525461-010|isbn=9789048525461 }}\n* ''Early Days of Greek Anarchism: The Democratic Club of Patras & Social Radicalism in Greece'' Edited and translated by Paul Pomonis. {{ISBN|1-873605-68-4}}\n* {{Cite thesis |last1=Iliopoulos |first1=Christos |title=Nietzsche & anarchism: an elective affinity, and a Nietzschean reading of the December 08 revolt in Athens |date=2014 |hdl=2134/16254 |hdl-access=free |language=en |publisher=[[Loughborough University]] |type=Ph.D. |df=mdy-all }}<!-- published in 2019 by Vernon Press: 978-1-62273-603-4 https://www.vernonpress.com/book/608 -->\n\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{Anarchism in Greece|state=expanded}}\n{{Anarchism}}\n\n[[Category:Anarchism by country|Greece]]\n[[Category:Anarchism in Greece| ]]\n", "name_user": "Greece666", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSources:missing parenthesis", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anarchism_in_Greece"}
{"title_page": "Italian submarine Ciro Menotti", "text_new": "{|{{Infobox ship begin\n}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image = \n| Ship caption = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header = \n| Ship country = [[Kingdom of Italy]]\n| Ship flag = {{shipboxflag|Kingdom of Italy|naval}}\n| Ship name = ''Ciro Menotti''\n| Ship namesake = \n| Ship ordered = \n| Ship awarded = \n| Ship builder = [[OTO Melara|Odero-Terni-Orlando]], [[Muggiano]]\n| Ship original cost = \n| Ship laid down = 1928\n| Ship launched = 29 December 1929\n| Ship completed = 1929\n| Ship commissioned = \n| Ship in service = \n| Ship fate = Scrapped 1 February 1948\n| Ship notes = \n| Ship badge = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header = \n| Header caption = \n| Ship class = {{sclass-|Bandiera|submarine}}\n| Ship displacement = *{{Cvt|925|LT|t|0|disp=flip|lk=on}} (surfaced)\n*{{Convert|1080|LT|t|0|disp=flip|abbr=on}} (submerged)\n| Ship length = {{convert|69.8|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship beam = {{convert|7.3|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship draft = {{convert|5.26|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship power = *{{cvt|3000|bhp|lk=on}} (diesels)\n*{{convert|1300|hp|abbr=on}} (electric motors)\n| Ship propulsion = *2 shafts; [[diesel-electric]]\n*2 \u00d7 [[diesel engine]]s\n*2 \u00d7 [[electric motor]]s\n| Ship speed = *{{convert|15|kn|lk=in}} (surfaced)\n*{{convert|8.2|kn}} (submerged)\n| Ship range = *{{convert|4750|nmi|abbr=on|lk=in}} at {{convert|8|kn}} (surfaced)\n*{{convert|60|nmi|abbr=on}} at {{convert|4|kn}} (submerged)\n| Ship test depth = {{cvt|90|m}}\n| Ship armament = *1 \u00d7 single [[Cannon 102/35 Model 1914|{{cvt|102|mm|in|0}}]] [[deck gun]]\n*2 \u00d7 single [[Breda Model 1931 Machine Gun|{{cvt|13.2|mm}}]] [[machine gun]]s\n*8 \u00d7 {{cvt|533|mm|0}} [[torpedo tube]]s (4 bow, 4 stern)\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Ciro Menotti''''' was one of four {{sclass-|Bandiera|submarine}} built for the {{lang|it|[[Regia Marina]]}} (Royal Italian Navy) during the late 1920s. Completed in 1929, she played a minor role in the [[Battle of M\u00e1laga|battle of Malaga]] during the [[Spanish Civil War]] of 1936\u20131939 supporting the [[Francoist Spain|Spanish Nationalists]]. ''Ciro Menotti'' carried out a number of resupply missions during [[World War II]]. \n\n==Design and description==\nThe ''Bandiera'' class was an improved and enlarged version of the preceding {{sclass-|Pisani|submarine}}s. They [[Displacement (ship)|displaced]] {{convert|925|LT|t|sp=us|lk=on|order=flip|0}} surfaced and {{convert|1080|LT|t|sp=us|order=flip|0}} submerged. The submarines were {{convert|69.8|m|ftin|sp=us}} long, had a [[beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|7.3|m|ftin|sp=us}} and a [[draft (hull)|draft]] of {{convert|5.26|m|ftin|sp=us}}.<ref name=c5/> They had a [[Submarine depth ratings|operational diving depth]] of {{convert|90|m|sp=us}}.<ref name=b4/> Their crew numbered 53 officers and enlisted men.<ref name=c5>Chesneau, p. 307</ref>\n\nFor surface running, the boats were powered by two {{convert|1500|bhp|lk=on|0|adj=on}} [[diesel engine]]s, each driving one [[propeller shaft]]. When submerged each propeller was driven by a {{convert|650|hp|0|adj=on}} [[electric motor]]. They could reach {{convert|15|kn|lk=in}} on the surface and {{convert|8.2|kn}} underwater.<ref name=b4/> On the surface, the ''Bandiera'' class had a range of {{convert|4750|nmi|lk=in}} at {{convert|8.5|kn}}; submerged, they had a range of {{convert|60|nmi|abbr=on}} at {{convert|4|kn}}.<ref name=b4>Bagnasco, p. 143</ref>\n\nThe boats were armed with eight {{convert|53.3|cm|in|0|adj=on|sp=us}} [[torpedo tube]]s, four each in the bow and stern for which they carried a total of 12 [[torpedo]]es. They were also armed with a single [[Cannon 102/35 Model 1914|{{convert|102|mm|in|0|adj=on|sp=us}}]] [[deck gun]] forward of the [[conning tower]] for combat on the surface. Their [[Anti-aircraft warfare|anti-aircraft armament]] consisted of two [[Breda Model 1931 Machine Gun|{{convert|13.2|mm|in|adj=on|sp=us}}]] [[machine gun]]s.<ref name=c5/><ref name=b4/>\n\n==Construction and career==\n''Ciro Menotti'' was [[laid down]] by [[OTO Melara|Odero-Terni-Orlando]] at their [[Muggiano]] [[shipyard]] in 1928, [[Ceremonial ship launching|launched]] on 29 December 1929 and completed later that year.<ref>Chesneau, pp. 307\u2013308</ref> During the Spanish Civil War, ''Ciro Menotti'' made a patrol off [[M\u00e1laga]] in early 1937 during which she sank the [[Second Spanish Republic|Republican]] {{GRT|1254|disp=adj}} [[mail steamer]] {{SS|Delfin|1885|6}} off [[Torrox]] on the night of 31 January\u20131 February. The submarine bombarded roads and bridges around M\u00e1laga over the next several days in support of the Nationalist assault on the city.<ref>Frank, p. 97</ref>\n\nAfter the entry of Italy in [[World War II]], ''Ciro Menotti'' was used in resupply missions to North Africa and [[Albania]] until 1942, when she was assigned for training. ''Ciro Menotti'' was interned at [[Malta]] in 1943 following the [[Armistice of Cassibile|Cassabile Armistice]], and finally scrapped on 1 February 1948.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Fitzsimons|first=Bernard|url=|title=The Illustrated encyclopedia of 20th century weapons and warfare|date=|publisher=Columbia House|year=1978|isbn=|location=|pages=270|language=en}}</ref> \n\n== Notes== \n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book|last=Bagnasco |first=Erminio |title=Submarines of World War Two |year=1977 |publisher=Naval Institute Press |location=Annapolis, Maryland |isbn=0-87021-962-6}} \n* {{cite book|last=Brescia|first=Maurizio|title=Mussolini's Navy: A Reference Guide to the Regina Marina 1930\u201345|year=2012|publisher=Naval Institute Press|location=Annapolis, Maryland|isbn=978-1-59114-544-8}}\n*{{cite book|title=Conway's All the World's Fighting Ships 1922\u20131946|editor1-last=Chesneau|editor1-first=Roger|publisher=Conway Maritime Press|location=Greenwich, UK|year=1980|isbn=0-85177-146-7}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Frank |first1=Willard C., Jr. |title=Question 12/88 |journal=Warship International |date=1989 |volume=XXVI |issue=1 |pages=95\u201397 |issn=0043-0374}}\n*{{cite book|last=Rohwer|first=J\u00fcrgen|title=Chronology of the War at Sea 1939\u20131945: The Naval History of World War Two|publisher=Naval Institute Press|location=Annapolis, Maryland|year=2005|edition=Third Revised|isbn=1-59114-119-2|authorlink=J\u00fcrgen Rohwer}}\n\n{{Bandiera-class submarine}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ciro Menotti}}\n[[Category:Ships built in La Spezia]]\n[[Category:Ships built by Oto Melara]]\n[[Category:Bandiera-class submarines]]\n[[Category:World War II submarines of Italy]]\n[[Category:1929 ships]]\n", "text_old": "{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image= \n|Ship caption= \n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country= [[Kingdom of Italy]]\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Kingdom of Italy|naval}}\n|Ship name= ''Ciro Menotti''\n|Ship namesake=\n|Ship ordered= \n|Ship awarded=\n|Ship builder=[[OTO Melara|Odero-Terni-Orlando]], [[Muggiano]]\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship laid down=1928\n|Ship launched=29 December 1929 \n|Ship completed= 1929\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship fate=Discarded, 1 February 1948\n|Ship notes=\n|Ship badge=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class={{sclass-|Bandiera|submarine}}\n|Ship displacement=*{{Cvt|925|LT|t|0|disp=flip|lk=on}} (surfaced)\n*{{Convert|1080|LT|t|0|disp=flip|abbr=on}} (submerged)\n|Ship length={{convert|69.8|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|7.3|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draft={{convert|5.26|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Ship power=*{{cvt|3000|bhp|lk=on}} (diesels)\n*{{convert|1300|hp|abbr=on}} (electric motors)\n|Ship propulsion=*2 shafts; [[diesel-electric]]\n*2 \u00d7 [[diesel engine]]s\n*2 \u00d7 [[electric motor]]s\n|Ship speed=*{{convert|15|kn|lk=in}} (surfaced)\n*{{convert|8.2|kn}} (submerged)\n|Ship range=*{{convert|4750|nmi|abbr=on|lk=in}} at {{convert|8|kn}} (surfaced)\n*{{convert|60|nmi|abbr=on}} at {{convert|4|kn}} (submerged)\n|Ship test depth={{cvt|90|m}}\n|Ship armament=*1 \u00d7 single [[Cannon 102/35 Model 1914|{{cvt|102|mm|in|0}}]] [[deck gun]]\n*2 \u00d7 single [[Breda Model 1931 Machine Gun|{{cvt|13.2|mm}}]] [[machine gun]]s\n*8 \u00d7 {{cvt|533|mm|0}} [[torpedo tube]]s (4 bow, 4 stern)\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Ciro Menotti''''' was one of four {{sclass-|Bandiera|submarine}} built for the {{lang|it|[[Regia Marina]]}} (Royal Italian Navy) during the late 1920s. Completed in 1929, she played a minor role in the [[Battle of M\u00e1laga|battle of Malaga]] during the [[Spanish Civil War]] of 1936\u20131939 supporting the [[Francoist Spain|Spanish Nationalists]]. ''Ciro Menotti'' carried out a number of resupply missions during [[World War II]]. \n\n==Design and description==\nThe ''Bandiera'' class was an improved and enlarged version of the preceding {{sclass-|Pisani|submarine}}s. They [[Displacement (ship)|displaced]] {{convert|925|LT|t|sp=us|lk=on|order=flip|0}} surfaced and {{convert|1080|LT|t|sp=us|order=flip|0}} submerged. The submarines were {{convert|69.8|m|ftin|sp=us}} long, had a [[beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|7.3|m|ftin|sp=us}} and a [[draft (hull)|draft]] of {{convert|5.26|m|ftin|sp=us}}.<ref name=c5/> They had a [[Submarine depth ratings|operational diving depth]] of {{convert|90|m|sp=us}}.<ref name=b4/> Their crew numbered 53 officers and enlisted men.<ref name=c5>Chesneau, p. 307</ref>\n\nFor surface running, the boats were powered by two {{convert|1500|bhp|lk=on|0|adj=on}} [[diesel engine]]s, each driving one [[propeller shaft]]. When submerged each propeller was driven by a {{convert|650|hp|0|adj=on}} [[electric motor]]. They could reach {{convert|15|kn|lk=in}} on the surface and {{convert|8.2|kn}} underwater.<ref name=b4/> On the surface, the ''Bandiera'' class had a range of {{convert|4750|nmi|lk=in}} at {{convert|8.5|kn}}; submerged, they had a range of {{convert|60|nmi|abbr=on}} at {{convert|4|kn}}.<ref name=b4>Bagnasco, p. 143</ref>\n\nThe boats were armed with eight {{convert|53.3|cm|in|0|adj=on|sp=us}} [[torpedo tube]]s, four each in the bow and stern for which they carried a total of 12 [[torpedo]]es. They were also armed with a single [[Cannon 102/35 Model 1914|{{convert|102|mm|in|0|adj=on|sp=us}}]] [[deck gun]] forward of the [[conning tower]] for combat on the surface. Their [[Anti-aircraft warfare|anti-aircraft armament]] consisted of two [[Breda Model 1931 Machine Gun|{{convert|13.2|mm|in|adj=on|sp=us}}]] [[machine gun]]s.<ref name=c5/><ref name=b4/>\n\n==Construction and career==\n''Ciro Menotti'' was [[laid down]] by [[OTO Melara|Odero-Terni-Orlando]] at their [[Muggiano]] [[shipyard]] in 1928, [[Ceremonial ship launching|launched]] on 29 December 1929 and completed later that year.<ref>Chesneau, pp. 307\u2013308</ref> During the Spanish Civil War, ''Ciro Menotti'' made a patrol off [[M\u00e1laga]] in early 1937 during which she sank the [[Second Spanish Republic|Republican]] {{GRT|1254|disp=adj}} [[mail steamer]] {{SS|Delfin|1885|6}} off [[Torrox]] on the night of 31 January\u20131 February. The submarine bombarded roads and bridges around M\u00e1laga over the next several days in support of the Nationalist assault on the city.<ref>Frank, p. 97</ref>\n\nAfter the entry of Italy in [[World War II]], ''Ciro Menotti'' was used in resupply missions to North Africa and [[Albania]] until 1942, when she was assigned for training. ''Ciro Menotti'' was interned at [[Malta]] in 1943 following the [[Armistice of Cassibile|Cassabile Armistice]], and finally scrapped on 1 February 1948.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Fitzsimons|first=Bernard|url=|title=The Illustrated encyclopedia of 20th century weapons and warfare|date=|publisher=Columbia House|year=1978|isbn=|location=|pages=270|language=en}}</ref> \n\n== Notes== \n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book|last=Bagnasco |first=Erminio |title=Submarines of World War Two |year=1977 |publisher=Naval Institute Press |location=Annapolis, Maryland |isbn=0-87021-962-6}} \n* {{cite book|last=Brescia|first=Maurizio|title=Mussolini's Navy: A Reference Guide to the Regina Marina 1930\u201345|year=2012|publisher=Naval Institute Press|location=Annapolis, Maryland|isbn=978-1-59114-544-8}}\n*{{cite book|title=Conway's All the World's Fighting Ships 1922\u20131946|editor1-last=Chesneau|editor1-first=Roger|publisher=Conway Maritime Press|location=Greenwich, UK|year=1980|isbn=0-85177-146-7}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Frank |first1=Willard C., Jr. |title=Question 12/88 |journal=Warship International |date=1989 |volume=XXVI |issue=1 |pages=95\u201397 |issn=0043-0374}}\n*{{cite book|last=Rohwer|first=J\u00fcrgen|title=Chronology of the War at Sea 1939\u20131945: The Naval History of World War Two|publisher=Naval Institute Press|location=Annapolis, Maryland|year=2005|edition=Third Revised|isbn=1-59114-119-2|authorlink=J\u00fcrgen Rohwer}}\n\n{{Bandiera-class submarine}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ciro Menotti}}\n[[Category:Ships built in La Spezia]]\n[[Category:Ships built by Oto Melara]]\n[[Category:Bandiera-class submarines]]\n[[Category:World War II submarines of Italy]]\n[[Category:1929 ships]]\n", "name_user": "DagosNavy", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Italian_submarine_Ciro_Menotti"}
{"title_page": "Noel Gallagher", "text_new": "Noel is a boring! He don\u2019t give the people what they want! Stop getting that woman to play them scissors and get oasis back! \n\n\n\n\n\nGallagher at Razzmatazz, Barcelona, Spain-5March2012 (3).jpg\n<!-- NOTE: Do not replace Noel Gallagher at Razzmatazz, Barcelona, Spain-5March2012 (3).jpg unless it is with a photo under a public domain or free license (meaning NOT fair use). Any fair use photos (i.e. 'promotional photos') violate the Fair Use Policy and will be deleted. See [[Wikipedia:Fair]] use criteria -->\n| caption            = Gallagher performing in March 2012\n| birth_name         = <!--Leave this blank as he is not known by a stage name.-->\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1967|5|29|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Manchester]], England<!--Just city and country if it's a major city.-->\n| occupation         = Singer, songwriter, musician<!--Please do not add to this list without first discussing your proposal on the talk page. -->\n| spouse             = {{ubl|{{marriage|Meg Mathews<br />|1997|2001|end=divorced}}|{{marriage|Sara MacDonald<br />|2011}}}}\n| children           = 3\n| relatives          = [[Liam Gallagher]] (brother)\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background      = solo_singer\n| genre           = {{hlist|[[Rock music|Rock]]|[[Britpop]]|[[alternative rock]]|[[psychedelic rock]]|[[baroque pop]]}}\n| instrument      = {{hlist|Vocals|guitar|bass guitar|drums}}<!--- If you think an instrument should be listed or removed, a discussion to reach consensus is needed first per: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_musical_artist#instrument--->\n| years_active    = 1991\u2013present\n| label           = {{hlist|[[Creation Records|Creation]]|[[Big Brother Recordings|Big Brother]]|[[Epic Records|Epic]]|Sour Mash}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n*[[Oasis (band)|Oasis]]\n*[[Noel Gallagher's High Flying Birds]]\n*[[Inspiral Carpets]]\n*[[The Chemical Brothers]]\n*[[Ian Brown]]\n*[[Paul Weller]]<!--Please do not add to this list without first discussing your proposal on the talk page. -->\n}}\n}}\n| website         = {{URL|noelgallagher.com}}\n}}\n'''Noel Thomas David Gallagher''' (born 29 May 1967) is an English singer, songwriter, and musician who holds both British and Irish citizenship.<ref>https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/showbiz-news/noel-gallagher-admits-applied-irish-17487767</ref> He served as the primary lyricist, lead guitarist, and co-lead vocalist of the rock band [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]]. After leaving Oasis in 2009, he formed and became the lead vocalist, guitarist, and lyricist for [[Noel Gallagher's High Flying Birds]].\n\nGallagher began playing guitar at the age of 13, and became a roadie and technician for [[Inspiral Carpets]] at the age of 21. He learned that his brother [[Liam Gallagher|Liam]] had formed a band called The Rain, which eventually became Oasis, and Liam invited him to join them as the lead guitarist. He agreed on condition that he would write their material. The band's debut album, ''[[Definitely Maybe]]'' (1994), was a critical and commercial success. Their second album, ''[[(What's the Story) Morning Glory?]]'' (1995), reached the top of the album charts in many countries, and their third studio album, ''[[Be Here Now (album)|Be Here Now]]'' (1997), became the fastest-selling album in UK chart history. [[Britpop]] eventually declined in popularity and Oasis failed to revive it, though their final two albums, ''[[Don't Believe the Truth]]'' (2005) and ''[[Dig Out Your Soul]]'' (2008), were hailed as their best efforts in over a decade. In August 2009, following an altercation with Liam, Noel announced his departure from Oasis and formed High Flying Birds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/oasis/48012 |title=Noel Gallagher confirms solo career plan &#124; News |work=NME |accessdate=5 April 2010}}</ref> Gallagher would go on to form Noel Gallagher's High Flying Birds, with whom he has released three studio albums.\n\nOasis' time was marked by turbulence, especially during the peak of Britpop, during which Noel was involved in several disputes with Liam and their fights and wild lifestyles regularly made tabloid headlines. The band notably had a rivalry with fellow Britpop band [[Blur (band)|Blur]]. Noel himself was often regarded as the spearhead of the Britpop movement, with ''[[NME]]'' deeming several Britpop bands (including [[Kula Shaker]], [[Ocean Colour Scene]], and [[Cast (band)|Cast]]) \"Noelrock\".<ref name=\"Kessler, Ted 1996\">Kessler, Ted. \"Noelrock!\" ''NME''. 8 June 1996.</ref> Many have praised his songwriting, with [[The Beatles|Beatles]] producer [[George Martin]] calling him \"the finest songwriter of his generation\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oasisinet.com/NewsArticle.aspx?n=801 |title=Time Flies \u2013 1994\u20132009 |work=Oasisnet |accessdate=12 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100414101646/http://www.oasisinet.com/NewsArticle.aspx?n=801 |archivedate=14 April 2010 }}</ref> Conversely, he was voted the most overrated guitarist of the last millennium in a 1999 poll,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12203950.Gallagher_and_the_Spice_Girls_have_little_to_celebrate_after_a_bad_day_at_the_polls_Discord_on_the_first_Noel/|title=Gallagher and the Spice Girls have little to celebrate after a bad day at the polls Discord on the first Noel|date=6 December 1999|website=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]|access-date=12 February 2017}}</ref> and the ninth most overrated ever in a 2002 listener survey.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Black|first=Edward|date=23 April 2002|title=Clapton rocked by guitar poll finding|journal=[[The Scotsman]]|quote=Fans polled by the music magazine ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]'' [...] Most over-rated: 1. Eric Clapton 2. Mark Knopfler 3. Hank Marvin 4. Keith Richards 5. Pete Townshend 6. The Edge 7. Carlos Santana 8. Brian 9 May. Noel Gallagher 10. Ronnie Wood.}}</ref> He cited the former as the award he most enjoyed receiving.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2009/mar/08/noel-gallagher-oasis|title=Did I say that? The words of Noel Gallagher, musician, 41|date=8 March 2009|website=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=12 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:The street where the Gallagher brothers used to live - panoramio.jpg|alt=A short streetside|thumb|Cranwell Drive in [[Burnage]], where the Gallaghers lived]]\nNoel Thomas David Gallagher was born in the [[Longsight]] area of [[Manchester]] on 29 May 1967, the son of Irish Catholic parents Peggy (n\u00e9e Sweeney) and Thomas Gallagher.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.esquire.co.uk/culture/news/a9081/noel-gallagher-is-esquires-december-cover-star/|title=Britain's Most Outspoken Rock Star|date=5 November 2015|newspaper=Esquire|access-date=12 February 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mayonews.ie/news/5722-oasis-for-charlestown|title=Oasis for Charlestown|date=13 January 2009|newspaper=The Mayo News|access-date=7 February 2019|language=en}}</ref> Aside from [[Liam Gallagher|Liam]], he also has an elder brother named Paul. Shortly after Liam's birth in 1972, the Gallaghers moved to Ashby Avenue and then Cranwell Drive in the Manchester suburb of [[Burnage]].<ref name=\"britpop118\">Harris, John. ''Britpop!: Cool Britannia and the Spectacular Demise of English Rock''. Da Capo Press, 2004. Pg. 118. {{ISBN|0-306-81367-X}}</ref> Gallagher had an unhappy childhood; he and his brothers were often beaten by their father, who was an alcoholic,<ref name=VH1>\"Oasis\". ''Behind the Music'', [[VH1]]. 2000.</ref> and he was often reclusive. Liam described him as \"the weirdo in the family\". Due to their unease around their father, he and Paul both developed [[stammer]]s.<ref name=\"britpop118\" /> As the oldest child, Paul was given a room to himself, while Noel was forced to share with Liam.<ref name=VH1/> Peggy acquired legal separation from her husband in 1976. She finally left him in 1982, taking her three sons with her.<ref name=\"britpop118\" />\n\nAs teenagers, the Gallagher brothers (especially Noel) were regular [[Truancy|truants]], often getting into trouble with the police. When his mother took a job in the school canteen, Gallagher ensured that he stopped by to visit her during lunch before skipping the rest of the day.<ref name=\"britpop119\">Harris, pg. 119</ref> He was expelled from school at the age of 15 for throwing a bag of flour over a teacher.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/dec/06/noel-gallagher-oasis|title=Interview: Noel Gallagher talks Oasis past and present|work=The Guardian|date=6 December 2008|accessdate=28 June 2009 | location=London | first=Simon | last=Hattenstone}}</ref> He used to hang around with the [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] [[List of hooligan firms|hooligan firms]] Maine Line Crew, Under-5s, and Young Guvnors in the 1980s,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/oasis-336-1323227|title=Noel Gallagher admits to football hooligan past &#124; NME|date=6 January 2009}}</ref> and received six months' probation at the age of 13 for robbing a corner shop.<ref name=VH1/> It was during this period of probation, with little else to do, that he first began to teach himself to play the guitar his father had left him. He would play his favourite songs from the radio, and was particularly inspired by the debut of [[the Smiths]] on ''[[Top of the Pops]]'' in 1983, performing their single \"[[This Charming Man]]\". He later said that, from that day on, he \"wanted to be [[Johnny Marr]]\".<ref>Harris, pg. 120</ref> He also appeared (and scored) for Manchester [[Gaelic football]] team [[CLG Ois\u00edn]] at [[Croke Park]] in [[Dublin]] in 1983.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.balls.ie/gaa/noel-gallagher-claims-he-scored-a-point-in-croke-park-as-a-teenager-301941|title=Noel Gallagher Tells Of How He Scored A Point In Croke Park As A Teenager|first=Conor|last=Neville|website=Balls.ie}}</ref>\n\nAs teenagers, the Gallagher brothers maintained limited contact with their father and secured jobs in construction. However, the relationship between father and sons continued to be tempestuous; Gallagher said, \"Because we were always arguing, we'd still be working at nine o'clock every night.\"<ref name=\"britpop119\" /> Having left his father's building company, he took a job at another building firm sub-contracted to [[British Gas]]. He sustained an injury when a heavy cap from a steel gas pipe landed on his right foot. Following a period of recuperation, he was offered a less physically demanding role in the company's storehouse, freeing up time for him to practise the guitar and write songs. He claimed to have written at least three of the songs on ''[[Definitely Maybe]]'' in this storehouse, including \"[[Live Forever (Oasis song)|Live Forever]]\". He later called the storehouse \"The Hit Hut\" and claimed the walls were painted gold.<ref name=\"dvd\"/> Much of the late 1980s found Gallagher unemployed and living in a bedsit, occupying his time by using recreational drugs, writing songs, and playing the guitar. He is left-handed, but plays right-handed.<ref>This is cited at many sources, including an interview with VH1's Behind the Music (2000), [[Russell Brand]] on ''[[1 Leicester Square]]'' (2006) and ''Oasis: In Their Own Words'' (1996)</ref>\n\nIn May 1988, Gallagher met guitarist Graham Lambert of [[Inspiral Carpets]] during a [[The Stone Roses|Stone Roses]] show. The two became acquainted and Gallagher became a regular at Inspiral Carpets shows. When he heard singer Steve Holt was leaving the band, he auditioned to be the new vocalist.<ref name=\"britpop121\">Harris, pg. 121</ref> He was unsuccessful, but became part of the band's road crew for the next two years. He struck up a friendship with monitor engineer Mark Coyle over their love of [[the Beatles]], and the pair spent soundchecks dissecting the group's songs.<ref name=\"britpop123\">Harris, pg. 123</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Oasis===\nIn 1991, Gallagher returned from an American tour with the Inspiral Carpets to find that his brother Liam had become a singer with a local band called [[The Rain (Manchester band)|the Rain]]. He attended one of their concerts at Manchester's Boardwalk but was unimpressed by the group's act. After rejecting an offer from Liam to be the band's manager,<ref>Interview with [[Frank Skinner]], ''The Frank Skinner Show'', 2000</ref> Gallagher agreed to join the band, on the condition that he would take creative control of the group and become its sole songwriter. According to another source, Gallagher told Liam and the rest of the group after having heard them play for the first time: \"Let me write your songs and I'll take you to superstardom, or else you'll rot here in Manchester\". His control over the band in its early years earned him the nickname \"The Chief\".<ref name=\"book\">{{cite book | author=Robertson, Ian | title=Oasis: What's the Story? | publisher=Blake Books | year=1996 | isbn=0-7119-5695-2}}</ref>\n\nIn May 1993, the band heard that a record executive from [[Creation Records]] would be scouting for talent at [[King Tut's Wah Wah Hut|King Tut's]] in Glasgow. Together, they found the money to hire a van and make the six-hour journey. When they arrived, they were refused entry to the club because no one notified the venue that Oasis had been added to the bill. The band eventually secured the opening slot and played a four-song set that impressed Creation founder [[Alan McGee]].<ref>Harris, pg.&nbsp;128\u201329</ref>\n\nMcGee then took the ''[[Live Demonstration]]'' tape to Sony America and invited Oasis to meet with him a week later in London, at which point they were signed to a six-album contract. Gallagher has since claimed that he only had six songs written at the time, and has put his success in the interview down to \"bullshitting\".<ref name=VH1/> However, McGee believes that when they met, Gallagher had fifty or so songs written, and merely lied about how prolific he had been following the contract.<ref name=\"dvd\" /> [[Richard Ashcroft]] was so impressed with Oasis during the time, that he invited them to tour with his band [[the Verve]] as an opening act.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicsaves.org/verve/interviews/37.shtml |title=Bittersweet Triumph |publisher=Musicsaves.org |accessdate=9 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nGallagher claimed to have written Oasis' first single, \"[[Supersonic (Oasis song)|Supersonic]]\", in \"the time it takes to play the song.\"<ref name=\"dvd\">{{cite video | people=Carruthers, Dick (Director) | date=2004 | title=Definitely Maybe  | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0477053/ | medium=VHS/DVD | publisher=Sony}}</ref> \"Supersonic\" was released in early 1994 and peaked at No. 31 on the official UK charts. The single was later followed by Oasis' debut album ''Definitely Maybe'', which was released in August 1994 and was a critical and commercial success.\n\nIt became the fastest-selling debut album in British history at the time and entered the UK charts at number one.<ref name=\"wts1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.100xr.com/100_XR/Artists/O/Oasis.htm |title=Oasis Biography, Music News, Discography @ 100 XR \u2013 No. 1 Rock Web Station!!! |publisher=100xr.com |accessdate=23 October 2011}}</ref> Despite their rapidly growing popularity, Gallagher briefly left Oasis in 1994 during their first American tour. The conditions were poor, and he felt the American audience\u2014still preoccupied with [[grunge]] and [[Heavy metal music|metal]]\u2014did not understand the band.<ref name=\"ownwords\"/> Gallagher stated that his early songs, especially \"Live Forever\", were written to refute grunge's pessimism.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.blender.com/guide/articles.aspx?id=2415 |title=The Greatest Songs Ever! Live Forever |last=Milner |first=Greg |magazine=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]] |date=January\u2013February 2007 |accessdate=18 February 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013131721/http://blender.com/guide/articles.aspx?id=2415 |archivedate=13 October 2007 }}</ref> Tensions mounted between him and Liam, culminating in a fight after a disastrous gig in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"dvd\" /> Having effectively decided to quit the music industry, he flew to San Francisco without telling the band, management or the crew. It was during this time that Gallagher wrote \"[[Talk Tonight]]\" as a \"thank you\" for the girl he stayed with, who \"talked him from off the ledge\". He was tracked down by Creation's Tim Abbot, and during a trip by the pair to Las Vegas, Gallagher decided to continue with the band. He reconciled with his brother and the tour resumed in [[Minneapolis]].<ref>Harris, pg. 189</ref>\n\nGallagher followed up the debut in 1995 with Oasis' first UK number-one single in \"[[Some Might Say]]\". This preceded their second album, ''(What's the Story) Morning Glory?'', released later that year. Though it suffered initial critical apathy, the album became the second fastest-selling album ever in the UK, entering the UK album charts at number one and peaking at number four on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart.<ref name=\"wts1\" />\n\nThe success of Oasis and his newfound fame and fortune were not lost on Gallagher, and both he and his brother became famous for their \"rock and roll lifestyle\". They drank heavily, abused drugs, fought fans, critics, peers, and each other, and made celebrity friends such as [[Ian Brown]], [[Paul Weller (singer)|Paul Weller]], [[Gary Mournfield|Mani]], [[Mick Jagger]], [[Craig Cash]], [[Kate Moss]] and [[Johnny Depp]]. Gallagher spent extravagantly, buying various cars and a swimming pool, despite the fact he can neither drive<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2004/09_september/10/ross_gallagher.shtml|title=Noel Gallagher on ten years of Oasis \u2013 exclusive interview|publisher=[[Friday Night with Jonathan Ross]]|accessdate=18 February 2008|date=10 September 2004|quote=I can't drive, but it didn't stop me buying five cars.}}</ref> nor swim.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2006/11/07/best-oasis-qa-ever-noel-gallagher-discusses-his-issues-with-canada-lars-ulrich/|title=Best Oasis Q&A Ever: Noel Gallagher Discusses His Issues With Canada, Lars Ulrich|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=18 February 2008|date=7 November 2006|quote=\"We're just having a bet over there and my mate reckons that you couldn't swim the English Channel.\" Now I can't swim, but I'd still give it a go.|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080220080229/http://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2006/11/07/best-oasis-qa-ever-noel-gallagher-discusses-his-issues-with-canada-lars-ulrich/ |archivedate = 20 February 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> He named his house in [[Belsize Park]] in London \"Supernova Heights\" (after the song \"[[Champagne Supernova]]\"), and his two cats \"Benson\" and \"Hedges\" after his favourite brand of cigarettes.<ref>1997 report on London News</ref> \"He's afraid this is true. He's also afraid that he was very high during the 90s and drunk most of the time. He can only tell you that it was a fucking brilliant time in his life, and he was naming everything after everything. Naming cats after cigarettes, though ... One of his finer moments, he must say.\"{{efn|A YouTube video showed this quote being written by Noel Gallagher personally on Wikipedia during a social media-inspired interview by ''[[GQ]]'' where Gallagher, who himself does not use social media, took to the internet to confirm and deny particular comments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6UYQnpDT1UM|title=Noel Gallagher Goes Undercover on Reddit, YouTube, Twitter and Instagram - Actually Me|newspaper=[[GQ]]|date=5 December 2017}}</ref>}}\n\nOasis went on to have greater success with their next two singles, \"[[Wonderwall (song)|Wonderwall]]\" and \"[[Don't Look Back in Anger]]\" charting at number two and number one respectively; the former becoming their sole top 10 hit in the US. Originally, Noel had wanted to take lead vocals on \"Wonderwall\", but Liam insisted on singing it. As compensation, Noel decided he would sing lead vocals on \"Don't Look Back in Anger\".<ref>Interview at ''[[Soccer AM]]'' (Sky Sports 1), 11 September 2004</ref> 1995 also saw Gallagher play two songs for the charity album ''[[The Help Album|Help!]]'': \"Fade Away\", accompanied by friend and Oasis fan Johnny Depp and Depp's then-girlfriend Kate Moss; and the Beatles' 1969 hit \"[[Come Together]]\", along with Paul Weller, [[Paul McCartney]] and others in a [[supergroup (bands)|supergroup]] called Smokin' Mojo Filters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.warchildmusic.com/helpbytrack.asp|title=The Help Album: Track By Track|publisher=[[War Child (charity)|War Child]]|accessdate=18 February 2008}}</ref> He began collaborating with the [[Chemical Brothers]], [[Ian Brown]], [[the Stands]], [[the Prodigy]] and Weller, amongst others. Gallagher became so influential that a June 1996 ''NME'' article argued that \"If Noel Gallagher, the most successful songwriter of his generation, champions a group, then said group are guaranteed more mainstream kudos and, quite possibly, more sales. And since Noel has taken to championing only five or six groups, then it's a powerful cabal he's promoting.\"<ref name=\"Kessler, Ted 1996\"/> The ''NME'' article grouped the bands Gallagher praised, including [[the Boo Radleys]], [[Ocean Colour Scene]], and [[Cast (band)|Cast]], under the banner of \"[[Noelrock]]\". John Harris typified these bands, and Gallagher, of \"sharing a dewy-eyed love of the 1960s, a spurning of much beyond rock's most basic ingredients, and a belief in the supremacy of 'real music'\".<ref>Harris, pg. 296</ref>\n\nIn March 1996, Gallagher and his brother Liam met their father again when the ''[[News of the World]]'' paid him to go to their hotel during a tour. He left for his room, later commenting \"as far as I'm concerned, I haven't got a father. He's not a father to me, y'know? I don't respect him in any way whatsoever\".<ref name=VH1/> In August 1996, Oasis sold out two nights at [[Concerts at Knebworth House|Knebworth]], playing to over 250,000 fans. Following the worldwide success of ''Morning Glory?'', ''[[Be Here Now (album)|Be Here Now]]'' (1997) became Oasis' most eagerly anticipated album to date. As with the previous two albums, all the tracks were written by Gallagher. After an initial blaze of publicity, positive critical reviews, and commercial success, the album failed to live up to long-term expectations, and public goodwill towards ''Be Here Now'' was short-lived.<ref>Cavanagh, David (2000). ''The Creation Records Story: My Magpie Eyes Are Hungry for the Prize''. (London) Virgin Books</ref> The album was ultimately regarded by many as a bloated, over-indulgent version of Oasis, which Gallagher has since blamed on the drug-addicted state and indifference of the band at the time.<ref name=liveforever>''Live Forever: The Rise and Fall of Brit Pop''. Passion Pictures, 2004.</ref> While the album was a recordbreaker, selling 813,000 copies in seven days, Gallagher has been critical of the album's popularity, saying: \"Just because you sell lots of records, it doesn't mean to say you're any good. Look at [[Phil Collins]].\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-24989044|title=1,000 Number ones: A chart history|work=BBC News|first=Mark|last=Savage|date=24 November 2013|accessdate=10 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nGallagher began to suffer drug-induced [[panic attack]]s during this period. His depression and paranoia inspired the song \"Gas Panic!\", subsequently included on the 2000 album ''[[Standing on the Shoulder of Giants]]''. He claimed to have quit using illicit drugs on 5 June 1998. Gallagher stated in 2001, \"I liked drugs, I was good at them. But I'd had panic attacks for about a year and I stopped because I wanted to. After you make the decision, it is quite easy.\" Of the period between 1993 and 1998, Gallagher claims, \"I can hardly remember a thing.\"<ref name=\"ownwords\">{{cite book | author=St. Michael, Mick | title=Oasis: In Their Own Words | publisher=Omnibus Pr | year=1996 | isbn=0-7119-5695-2}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Noel Gallagher.jpg|thumb|Gallagher performing with Oasis at the [[Shoreline Amphitheatre]] on 11 September 2005]]\nAfter the hype surrounding the release of ''Be Here Now'' had started to wane, critical response to the band became calmer and more considered, leading to a media backlash. In 1997, Gallagher was criticised for attending a high-profile and well-publicised media party at [[10 Downing Street]], hosted by the new Prime Minister, [[Tony Blair]], along with other celebrities and industry figures who had supported [[British Labour party|New Labour]] in the run-up to the general election. Liam and Blur's Damon Albarn declined their invitations, with Albarn commenting \"Enjoy the schmooze, comrade\".<ref>{{cite news | title=Timeline: Blur v Oasis after Britpop |work=BBC News  | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/music/4151510.stm| accessdate=16 August 2005 | date=16 August 2005}}</ref> The perception of Gallagher as someone now mixing with politicians and a famous photograph of him sipping champagne with Blair conflicted with the \"working class hero\" status championed through songs such as \"Up in the Sky\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.guardian.co.uk/music/2007/05/what_happened_to_rock_under_bl.html|title=What happened to rock under Blair?|work=The Guardian|last=Petridis|first=Alexis|date=10 May 2007|accessdate=18 February 2008 | location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, rhythm guitarist [[Paul Arthurs|Paul \"Bonehead\" Arthurs]] quit the band, with bassist [[Paul McGuigan (musician)|Paul McGuigan]] following soon afterwards. As a result, the fourth studio album, ''[[Standing on the Shoulder of Giants]]'', was recorded by just the Gallaghers and drummer [[Alan White (Oasis drummer)|Alan White]], with Gallagher playing all guitar parts. He later commented on Bonehead's departure, \"It's hardly Paul McCartney leaving the Beatles, is it?\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://arts.guardian.co.uk/glastonbury2004/story/0,,1242267,00.html|title=Not here now|work=The Guardian|date=19 June 2004|accessdate=14 January 2008 | location=London | first=John | last=Robinson}}</ref> After the recording sessions were completed, Gallagher selected [[Gem Archer]] to join in place of Bonehead.\n\nLater that year Alan McGee decided to leave Creation and sold the rest of his 51% stake in the label to Sony.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/536396.stm|title=Oasis record boss quits|publisher=BBC |date=25 November 1999|accessdate=18 February 2008}}</ref> Gallagher took this opportunity to set up [[Big Brother Recordings]], which took over Oasis' distribution in the UK, but Sony imprint [[Epic Records]] continued to handle the band's international distribution.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.yahoo.com/read/news/12045608|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070611092326/http://music.yahoo.com/read/news/12045608|title=Oasis Create Big Brother Records|date=5 January 2000|accessdate=18 February 2008|archivedate=11 June 2007|publisher=Yahoo!}}</ref> Around the time of the album's release, [[Andy Bell (musician)|Andy Bell]], formerly of [[Ride (band)|Ride]], joined the band as bassist. In 2001, Gallagher formed his label, Sour Mash Records, which released records by the likes of [http://www.shacknet.co.uk Shack] and [[Proud Mary (band)|Proud Mary]]. The incorporation of the label followed Gallagher's debut as a producer, working with Proud Mary on their debut, ''[[The Same Old Blues]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Davis|first=Darren|url=http://music.yahoo.com/read/news/12062958|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070616133906/http://music.yahoo.com/read/news/12062958|title=Oasis's Noel Gallagher Does The Sour Mash For Proud Mary|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=1 April 2001|accessdate=1 April 2008|archivedate=16 June 2007}}</ref> In 2003, Gallagher received songwriting credits from [[Girls Aloud]]'s single \"[[Life Got Cold]]\" due to the song's guitar riff being similar to \"[[Wonderwall (song)|Wonderwall]]\".\n\nIn late 2006, Gallagher toured the UK, Europe, Japan, America and Australia in a series of acclaimed intimate semi-acoustic gigs accompanied by Gem Archer and [[Terry Kirkbride]] on percussion. The show proved successful and a further series of sets took place in 2007. March 2007 saw Gallagher perform in Moscow\u2014the first time an Oasis member has performed in Russia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisislancashire.co.uk/display.var.1070004.0.noel_gallagher_lowry_salford.php|author=Bromby-Tavenner, Vida|date=4 December 2006|title=Noel Gallagher @ Lowry, Salford|accessdate=22 September 2007|publisher=thisislancashire.co.uk|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927172030/http://www.thisislancashire.co.uk/display.var.1070004.0.noel_gallagher_lowry_salford.php|archivedate=27 September 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Gallagher dismissed claims that he was planning to embark on a solo career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.news.launch.yahoo.com/dyna/article.html?a=/14022007/344/d-bigger-elvis-says-noel.html&e=l_news_dm|date=14 February 2007|title=I'd be bigger than Elvis says Noel|accessdate=21 September 2007|publisher=Yahoo Music}}</ref> In early 2007, Gallagher joined the rest of Oasis to collect the \"Outstanding Contribution to Music\" Award at the [[Brit Awards 2007]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allheadlinenews.com/articles/7006473035|title=Arctic Monkeys And Killers Named Top Winners at BRIT Awards|accessdate=21 September 2007|publisher=AHN|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926224405/http://www.allheadlinenews.com/articles/7006473035|archivedate=26 September 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nGallagher, along with the band recorded their seventh studio album between 2007 and the next year at [[Abbey Road Studios]] and in Los Angeles. At the end of the summer of 2008 the band began a tour that lasted 12 months. In March 2009, ''[[The Times]]'' in conjunction with iTunes released a selection of live recordings by Noel Gallagher taken from his semi-acoustic performance at the Royal Albert Hall on 27 March 2007 in aid of Teenage Cancer Trust. ''[[The Dreams We Have as Children \u2013 Live at the Royal Albert Hall|The Dreams We Have as Children]]'' features classic and rare tracks from the Oasis canon along with several cover versions of some of Gallagher's favourite artists.\n\nOn 28 August 2009, Gallagher quit Oasis after a fight with his brother, Liam. Shortly before midnight on Friday, Gallagher posted a statement on his message board called \"Tales from the Middle of Nowhere\" on the band's website announcing his departure.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oasisinet.com/DiaryArticle.aspx?n=113 |title=The Official Oasis website and fan community |publisher=Oasisinet |accessdate=23 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20091009193705/http://www.oasisinet.com/DiaryArticle.aspx?n=113 |archivedate=9 October 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Solo career and High Flying Birds===\n[[File:Noel Gallagher at Razzmatazz, Barcelona, Spain-5March2012 (6).jpg|thumb|right|upright|Noel Gallagher's High Flying Birds performing March 2012]]\nGallagher's first concerts without Oasis were announced on 1 February 2010<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hellomagazine.com/celebrities-news-in-pics/01-02-2010/53101/general/ |title=Noel Gallagher announces first post-Oasis gig &#124; Latest celebrity news |work=Hello! |accessdate=5 April 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606063827/http://www.hellomagazine.com/celebrities-news-in-pics/01-02-2010/53101/general/ |archive-date=6 June 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> to be at London's [[Royal Albert Hall]] on 25 and 26 March 2010 for Teenage Cancer Trust .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rttnews.com/ArticleView.aspx?Id=1199985&SMap=1 |title=Noel Gallagher Books First Solo Dates |publisher=Rttnews.com |date=3 February 2010 |accessdate=5 April 2010}}</ref> He was supported by [[the Courteeners]] and [[Plan B (rapper)|Plan B]] respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teenagecancertrust.org/who-we-are/media-centre/press-releases/teenage-cancer-trust-announces-support-acts-for-1/ |title=Teenage Cancer Trust announces support acts for 10th anniversary gigs at the Royal Albert Hall \u2013 Press Releases \u2013 Media centre \u2013 Teenage Cancer Trust |publisher=Teenagecancertrust.org |accessdate=5 April 2010}}</ref> [[Terry Kirkbride]] and [[Gem Archer]] joined him on-stage,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.musicrooms.net/alternative/4671-Noel-Gallagher-Plays-Oasis--Sides.html |title=Noel Gallagher Plays Oasis B-Sides |publisher=Musicrooms.net |date=26 March 2010 |accessdate=5 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100403093207/http://www.musicrooms.net/alternative/4671-Noel-Gallagher-Plays-Oasis--Sides.html |archivedate=3 April 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.live4ever.uk.com/2010/03/noel-gallagher-returns-for-teenage-cancer-trust/ |title=Noel Gallagher Returns For Teenage Cancer Trust &#124; Live4ever \u2013 The Brit Rock Daily |publisher=Live4ever.uk.com |date=25 March 2010 |accessdate=5 April 2010}}</ref> as did [[Jay Darlington]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/noel-gallagher/50378 |title=Noel Gallagher plays first post-Oasis gig in London |work=NME |accessdate=5 April 2010}}</ref> all of whom Gallagher had previously worked with while he was still a member of Oasis. He played a mostly acoustic set, and played a variety of Oasis album tracks and B-sides.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/music/article7076920.ece |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615092954/http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/music/article7076920.ece|archivedate=15 June 2011 |title=Noel Gallagher at the Royal Albert Hall, SW7|first=Pete|last=Paphides |work=The Times |date=26 March 2010 |accessdate=5 April 2010 |location=London}}</ref> It was almost the same set he played at the Royal Albert Hall in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://stopcryingyourheartoutnews.blogspot.com/2010/03/noel-gallagher-joined-by-ex-oasis-gem.html |title=Latest Oasis News With stopcryingyourheartout.com: Noel Gallagher Joined By Ex-Oasis Gem Archer For Teenage Cancer Trust Show |publisher=Stopcryingyourheartoutnews.blogspot.com |date=25 March 2010 |accessdate=5 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.live4ever.uk.com/2010/03/review-noel-gallagher-teenage-cancer-trust-show-royal-albert-hall/ |title=Review: Noel Gallagher \u2013 Teenage Cancer Trust Show, Royal Albert Hall &#124; Live4ever \u2013 The Brit Rock Daily |publisher=Live4ever.uk.com |date=26 March 2010 |accessdate=5 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Youngs |first=Ian |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/8588384.stm |title=Noel Gallagher begins solo life |work=BBC News  |date=26 March 2010 |accessdate=5 April 2010}}</ref> Gallagher also joined friend [[Paul Weller]] onstage in London on 21 April 2010, and played the Oasis song \"Mucky Fingers\" and a song he co-wrote with Weller, \"Echoes Round the Sun.\"\n\nGallagher confirmed that he would be returning to the studio in August 2010 to record drums for an unnamed artist, later confirmed to be Paul Weller. He also denied rumours that he would be the Best Man for [[Russell Brand]]'s marriage to [[Katy Perry]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/oasis/52523 |title=Noel Gallagher heading into the studio 'this week' |work=NME |location=UK |date=17 August 2010 |accessdate=17 August 2010}}</ref> In August, it was mentioned on a UK Music blog, Sourmash Music, that Gallagher had been working with Liverpool group the Sand Band. Lead singer David McDonnell has been co-writing with Gallagher and are looking to collaborate on future solo projects together.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sourmashmusic.com/2010/08/19/does-noel-gallagher-have-a-new-backing-band/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110129035709/http://sourmashmusic.com/2010/08/19/does-noel-gallagher-have-a-new-backing-band/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=29 January 2011 |title=Does Noel Gallagher have a new backing band? \u00ab Sourmash Music |publisher=Sourmashmusic.com |accessdate=23 October 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn 24 November 2010, [[Miles Kane]] revealed that Gallagher sang on a track from his debut solo album titled ''My Fantasy''. Kane also revealed that he will appear on Gallagher's forthcoming album, playing guitar.<ref>{{cite web|title=NME.com \u2013 Miles Kane reveals new Noel Gallagher album collaborations|url=http://www.nme.com/news/miles-kane/53970|accessdate=4 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 February 2011, Gallagher stated he had \"not even started\" his first solo record, despite Liam rumouring that he 'swiped' material from the ''[[Dig Out Your Soul]]'' sessions. \"I am not recording new stuff, not just yet,\" he said to [[Talksport]]. \"It'll be out when it's finished I guess. Well I've not even started it, so I don't know.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Sean Michaels |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/feb/10/noel-gallagher-denies-solo-album |title=Noel Gallagher: 'I am not recording new stuff' &#124; Music &#124; guardian.co.uk |work=Guardian |location=UK |accessdate=9 July 2011 |date=10 February 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Noel Gallagher 2.jpg|thumb|Noel Gallagher during FIB 2015]]\n[[Noel Gallagher's High Flying Birds]] released a [[Noel Gallagher's High Flying Birds (album)|self-titled album]] on 17 October 2011; a collaboration album with [[Amorphous Androgynous]] was to be released in 2012 but has now been shelved indefinitely.<ref>{{cite web|author=RETROFUZZ |url=http://www.noelgallagher.com |title=The Official Noel Gallagher Website &#124; Home |publisher=Noelgallagher.com |accessdate=23 October 2011}}</ref> He began touring in [[Dublin]] on 23 October 2011. The touring band announced for Noel Gallagher's High Flying Birds comprised David McDonnell (guitar), [[Russell Pritchard]] (bass), Mikey Rowe (keyboards) and [[Jeremy Stacey]] (drums); McDonnell left during rehearsals and was replaced before the tour with Tim Smith who had played with Rowe and Stacey previously.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.live4ever.uk.com/2011/08/noel-gallaghers-high-flying-birds-confirm-first-uk-tour-dates/ |title=Noel Gallagher's High Flying Birds Confirm First UK Tour Dates &#124; Live4ever Ezine |publisher=Live4ever.uk.com |date=2 August 2011 |accessdate=23 October 2011}}</ref> On 20 July 2011, Gallagher released a 47-second trailer of his first single \"[[The Death of You and Me]]\". The video for the debut single was released on 25 July at 8:21&nbsp;am (GMT).<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://thequietus.com/articles/06541-noel-gallagher-announces-solo-album |title=News &#124; Noel Gallagher Announces Two Solo Albums |magazine=The Quietus |accessdate=9 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the self-titled debut, Noel Gallagher's High Flying Birds released their second album ''[[Chasing Yesterday (album)|Chasing Yesterday]]'' 2 March 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Noel Gallagher announces new album 'Chasing Yesterday' LP|url= http://www.nme.com/news/noel-gallagher/80349|website=NME|publisher=NME|accessdate=19 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 Gallagher co-wrote \"Birth of an Accidental Hipster\" with Paul Weller for [[the Monkees]].\n\nIn June 2015, Noel Gallagher confirmed he was working on a third High Flying Birds album,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/noel-gallagher/86309|title=Noel Gallagher 'I'm already a bit of the way into the next record' LP|website=NME|publisher=NME|accessdate=19 June 2015}}</ref> later announced to be titled ''[[Who Built the Moon?]]'' and released on 27 November 2017.\n\nOn 9 September 2017, Gallagher along with his band served as the headline act of \"We Are Manchester,\" a benefit concert to mark the reopening of [[Manchester Arena]] (following [[Manchester Arena bombing|a terrorist attack there in May]]).\n\nOn 2 May 2019, the band released \"Black Star Dancing\", the title track of their EP, which was released on 14 June 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiox.co.uk/artists/noel-gallaghers-high-flying-birds/noel-gallagher-black-star-dancing-single-ep/|title=Noel Gallagher releases Black Star Dancing single|website=Radio X}}</ref> \n\nOn 5 August 2019, Gallagher's band released the title track \"This Is The Place\" for a second EP which was released on 27 September 2019. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/listen-noel-gallaghers-new-single-this-is-the-place-announces-ep-slates-liam-2535187|title=Listen to Noel Gallagher's new single 'This Is The Place' as he unveils EP|first=John|last=Earls|date=5 August 2019|website=NME}}</ref> \n\nIn August 2019, Gallagher toured the United States with [[The Smashing Pumpkins]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/smashing-pumpkins-and-noel-gallaghers-high-flying-birds-announce-tour/|title=Smashing Pumpkins and Noel Gallagher\u2019s High Flying Birds Announce Tour|website=Pitchfork}}</ref>\n\nGallagher appeared on First We Feast's \"Hot Ones\" in October 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NxZwXy8kds8|publisher=[[First We Feast]]|title=Noel Gallagher Looks Back in Anger at Spicy Wings|date=3 October 2019|accessdate=3 October 2019}}</ref>\nOn November 14th, 2019, Noel released a new single 'Wandering Star'. The single was released in promotion of his studio EP 'Blue Moon Rising'. The EP will also feature reflex and 7\" mixes of the title track and is set to be released on March 6th, 2020.\n\n===Other projects===\nIn an interview with ''[[NME]]'' in 2014 whilst promoting his solo debut album ''[[Everyday Robots]]'', [[Damon Albarn]] hinted at a collaborative project with Gallagher. Despite the years of animosity during [[Blur (band)|Blur]] and Oasis' respective heyday, Albarn said: \"We're talking. It's not anything to get excited about yet. I mean, he's doing his thing. He\u2019s finishing a new record. I've got my record coming out, but the principle of us making music together is something, you know. It would be fair to say, we have discussed it at least once.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://damonalbarn.tumblr.com/tagged/NME-is-obsessed-with-this|title=Enter Password|publisher=Damonalbarn.tumblr.com|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, Gallagher revealed that he was considering retirement from live shows within the following 10 years. He stated: \"It's not fun being on a bus for six weeks in America. It's fine when you're young, but I'm almost 50.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/noel-gallagher/83798|title=Noel Gallagher says he may retire from playing live within the next 'ten years'|publisher=NME|accessdate=23 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, Albarn's animated band [[Gorillaz]] released the track \"[[We Got the Power (Gorillaz song)|We Got the Power]]\" featuring Gallagher on backing vocals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2017/03/former-rivals-damon-albarn-and-noel-gallagher-record-together-for-first-time-on-gorillazs-weve-got-the-power-listen/ |title=Former rivals Damon Albarn and Noel Gallagher record together for first time on Gorillaz's \"We've Got the Power\" \u2014 listen |work=[[Consequence of Sound]] |date=23 March 2017 |accessdate=24 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n===Relationships===\nGallagher became engaged to his girlfriend Diane at the age of 18, but they never married and eventually separated. In 1988, he moved out of his family home to live with Louise Jones, whom he described as his \"soulmate\" and for whom he wrote \"[[Slide Away (Oasis song)|Slide Away]]\". They had an on-again, off-again relationship before separating in June 1994, with Gallagher stating, \"I don't think I'll ever get over it.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.allexperts.com/q/Oasis-542/Noel-Girlfriends.htm |title=Oasis: Noel's Girlfriends |publisher=En.AllExperts.com |accessdate=9 August 2009 |last1=Davidson |first1=Dougie |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091021052348/http://en.allexperts.com/q/Oasis-542/Noel-Girlfriends.htm |archivedate=21 October 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn June 1997, Gallagher married [[Meg Mathews]] in [[Las Vegas]]. He had met her in 1994 through her roommate, MTV presenter [[Rebecca de Ruvo]], whom he was dating at the time and whom he left for Mathews.<ref>{{cite video |date=June 1997 |title=The Howard Stern Show |url=http://imfeelingsupersonic.blogspot.com/2008/02/noel-gallagher-howard-stern-show-1997.html |format=Audio |publisher=WXRK |accessdate=28 June 2009}}</ref> Mathews gave birth to a daughter, Ana\u00efs Gallagher, on 27 January 2000. Gallagher and Mathews divorced in January 2001 on the grounds of his adultery with Scottish publicist Sara MacDonald, whom he met at [[Ibiza]] nightclub [[Space (Ibiza nightclub)|Space]] in June 2000. After the divorce was finalised, Gallagher claimed that he had never actually been unfaithful and had only claimed to have cheated on Mathews to speed up the divorce process.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/1125485.stm |title=Noel and Meg finally divorce|publisher=BBC  |date=19 January 2001 |accessdate=28 June 2009}}</ref>\n\nGallagher then began a relationship with MacDonald, and wrote \"Waiting for the Rapture\" about their meeting. They have two sons: Donovan Rory MacDonald Gallagher (born 22 September 2007)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7008537.stm |title=Gallagher becomes a father again |publisher=BBC  |date=22 September 2007 |accessdate=28 May 2009}}</ref> and Sonny Patrick MacDonald Gallagher (born 1 October 2010). They were married on 18 June 2011 in a private ceremony at the Lime Wood Hotel in [[New Forest National Park]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/jun/20/noel-gallagher-gets-married-liam|title=Noel Gallagher gets married without inviting Liam|newspaper=The Guardian|date=20 June 2011|accessdate=28 August 2011|location=London|first=Sean|last=Michaels}}</ref> His friend [[Russell Brand]] was the best man.<ref name=\":0\">{{Citation|last=GQ|title=Noel Gallagher Goes Undercover on Reddit, YouTube, Twitter and Instagram {{!}} Actually Me {{!}} GQ|date=2017-12-05|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6UYQnpDT1UM|access-date=2019-05-08}}</ref> They currently live in [[Hampshire]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiox.co.uk/artists/noel-gallaghers-high-flying-birds/moving-hampshire-stabbings-near-london-home/|title=Noel Gallagher's moving to Hampshire after stabbings near London home|website=Radio X}}</ref>\n\nGallagher is friends with [[Gary Mounfield]], [[Richard Ashcroft]] (to whom he dedicated the Oasis song \"[[(What's the Story) Morning Glory?|Cast No Shadow]]\"), the [[Chemical Brothers]],<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://oasisinterviews.blogspot.com/1995/09/noel-gallagher-nme-30th-september-1995.html|title=Morning Story|journal=NME|date=September 1995|first=Andy|last=Richardson|accessdate=13 August 2010}}</ref> [[John Lydon]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.johnlydon.com/SELECT.HTM|title=John Lydon official website|accessdate=28 June 2009}}</ref> [[Steve Jones (musician)|Steve Jones]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.live4ever.us/2008/11/mexico-steve-jones-and-wheres-ricky |title=The Oasis Newsroom |publisher=Live4ever.us |date=27 November 2008 |accessdate=9 August 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717181656/http://www.live4ever.us/2008/11/mexico-steve-jones-and-wheres-ricky |archivedate=17 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Kasabian]],<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/new/xmlfeed.nsf/mndwebpages/kasabian%20friends%20for%20life%20with%20oasis |title=Kasabian \u2013 Kasabian 'Friends For Life' With Oasis |magazine=Contactmusic.com |accessdate=9 August 2009}}</ref> [[Andy Nicholson]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2007/mar/05/news.libertines|title=Pete to Carl: Will you be my best man?|work=The Guardian |location=UK |date=15 March 2005|accessdate=17 August 2009 | first=Paul | last=MacInnes}}</ref> [[Ricky Hatton]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/oasis/41233|title=Oasis' Liam and Noel Gallagher join Ricky Hatton in Las Vegas|work=NME|date=23 November 2008|accessdate=17 August 2009}}</ref> [[Paul McCartney]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=Noel+Gallagher+on+Radio+1+-+01.12.08&search_type=&aq=-1&oq= |title=Noel Gallagher on Radio 1 |date=12 January 2008 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=9 August 2009}}</ref> [[Jamie Carragher]], [[Chris Martin]], [[Jonny Buckland]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://observer.guardian.co.uk/omm/story/0,,1507223,00.html |title=The Gallagher interview in full |work=The Observer |date=29 June 2009 |accessdate=9 August 2009 | location=London}}</ref> [[Johnny Marr]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stopcryingyourheartoutnews.blogspot.com/2008/09/when-johnny-marr-lent-noel-gallagher.html |title=Latest Oasis News With stopcryingyourheartout.com: When Johnny Marr Lent Noel Gallagher His Gibson Guitar |publisher=Stopcryingyourheartoutnews.blogspot.com |date=19 September 2008 |accessdate=9 August 2009}}</ref> [[Morrissey]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/music/interviews/a33449/noel-gallagher-morrissey-new-album/|title=Noel Gallagher on Getting Drunk with Morrissey|first=Jeff|last=Slate|date=3 March 2015|website=Esquire}}</ref> [[Bono]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/noel-gallagher-98-1217382|title=Noel Gallagher claims that Bono can drink more than Morrissey|first=Luke Morgan|last=Britton|date=18 May 2015|website=NME}}</ref> [[Paul Weller]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicfanclubs.org/oasis/totalguitarnoel.html |title=Total Guitar: Noel Gallagher |publisher=Musicfanclubs.org |accessdate=9 August 2009}}</ref> [[Johnny Depp]] (who played slide guitar on the Oasis song \"Fade In-Out\"),<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/new/xmlfeed.nsf/mndwebpages/oasis%20appearance%20depp.s%20career%20high |title=Johnny Depp \u2013 Oasis Appearance Depp's Career High |magazine=Contactmusic.com |accessdate=9 August 2009}}</ref> and [[Kate Moss]] (who used to stay with him when she was visiting London).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Xkyjf6xJSh4 |title=YouTube \u2013 Noel Gallagher on The Evening Session \u2013 20.08.96 \u2013 Part 2 |publisher=Uk.youtube.com |date=14 September 2008 |accessdate=9 August 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/oasis/41233 |title=Oasis' Liam and Noel Gallagher join Ricky Hatton in Las Vegas &#124; News |work=NME |accessdate=9 August 2009}}</ref> Around the time that actor [[Ewan McGregor]] found out he had been cast as [[Obi-Wan Kenobi]], Gallagher (his next-door neighbour) challenged him to a battle with toy [[lightsabers]] in his garden the morning after a party.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=y-bm1Xn7pmY|title=Lightsaber Fight Noel Gallagher v Ewan McGregor|via=www.youtube.com}}</ref>\n\n===Other===\nIn 1998, Gallagher made a cameo appearance as himself in an episode of ''[[The Young Person's Guide to Becoming a Rock Star]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=03ZZSsxnEh8|title=Noel Gallagher - Young Person's Guide To Becoming a Rockstar|via=www.youtube.com}}</ref> He was a frequent guest on ''[[The Russell Brand Show (radio show)|The Russell Brand Show]]'' on [[BBC Radio 2]], appearing on almost every show, leading Brand to dub him an unofficial \"co-presenter\".{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} He is also a regular on the digital radio sports show ''[[TalkSPORT]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.talksport.co.uk/radio/andy-goldsteins-sports-bar/130515/noel-gallagher-roberto-mancinis-sacking-man-city-manager-197608 |title=Noel Gallagher on Roberto Mancini's sacking as Man City manager |publisher=talkSPORT |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, Gallagher was reported to have an estimated personal fortune of \u00a325 million.<ref>{{cite news|last=Laville |first=Sandra |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1314112/Noel-Gallaghers-wife-wants-10m-divorce-deal.html |title=Noel Gallagher's wife wants \u00a310m divorce deal |work=Daily Telegraph |date=10 January 2001 |accessdate=9 August 2009 | location=London}}</ref> In 2009, ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' Rich List estimated his and Liam's combined personal fortune at \u00a352 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mog.com/blog_post/content/1032/1285776 |title=Oasis' Gallagher Brothers Weather Economic Storm \u2013 Worth 52 million |publisher=Mog.com |accessdate=21 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090503114433/http://mog.com/blog_post/content/1032/1285776 |archivedate=3 May 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nGallagher is a lifelong [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City FC]] supporter, admitting he \"cried like a baby\" when they won the [[2011\u201312 Premier League]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18055827 |title=Manchester City fan Noel Gallagher on 'mind-blowing' victory |publisher=BBC |date=14 May 2012 |accessdate=14 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://fourfourtwo.com/interviews/celebrityfans/192/article.aspx/7595458.stm|title=Gallagher on 'staggering' City takeover|publisher=BBC|date=3 September 2008|accessdate=28 June 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120710084511/http://fourfourtwo.com/interviews/celebrityfans/192/article.aspx/7595458.stm|archivedate=10 July 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He is a friend of the team's former midfielder [[Joey Barton]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/manchester_city/s/1009/1009076_its_pure_city_says_noel.html|date=13 June 2007|accessdate=22 July 2007|title='It's pure City' says Noel| last=Whalley|first=Mike|work=Manchester Evening News}}</ref> as well as Italian striker [[Alessandro Del Piero]], who described Gallagher as Italy's \"lucky mascot\" during the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw-world.de/dw/article/0,,2082415,00.html|title=Oasis Rocker Gallagher Revealed as Del Piero's Lucky Mascot|publisher=[[Deutsche Welle]]|date=7 July 2006|accessdate=28 June 2009}}</ref> and appears in the video for Oasis' \"[[Lord Don't Slow Me Down (song)|Lord Don't Slow Me Down]]\".{{cn|date=January 2020}} Gallagher and Kasabian lead guitarist [[Sergio Pizzorno]] took part in drawing teams for the [[FA Cup]] third round in 2011. Coincidentally, Pizzorno drew his hometown team [[Leicester City]] with Gallagher's Manchester City for the third round tie, in which both teams drew 2-2 and Manchester City proceeded to win 4-2 in the replay. He participated in the unveiling of [[Umbro]]-sponsored football kits with captain [[Vincent Kompany]]. In the advertising campaign, the two men are pictured wearing the new Manchester City home and away shirts for the 2012\u201313 season. Formerly, Kompany had introduced Gallagher to 80,000 fans during the [[Rock Werchter]] music festival in Belgium.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.brandrepublic.com/news/1139845/|date=6 July 2012|accessdate=6 July 2012|title=Noel Gallagher and Manchester City's Kompany unveil new Umbro kits| last=Durrani|first=Arif|work=Brand Republic}}</ref>\n\nThe son of Irish immigrants, Gallagher supports the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Irish national football team]] and has said that he does not consider himself \"to be English at all\".<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.irishpost.co.uk/entertainment/interview-unstoppable-noel-gallagher | title= Interview: The Unstoppable Noel Gallagher | work=Irish Post | first=Richard | last=Purden | date=3 March 2015 | accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref> Nevertheless, he did serve as an official ambassador for England's bid to host the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/8934838.stm | title= Nick Clegg hails England's 'unbeatable' World Cup bid |work=BBC News  | date=23 August 2010}}</ref> Gallagher is also a fan of the [[National Football League]], noting in an [[ESPN]] interview, \"I love the NFL. I don't have a team ''per se'', but I'm into it. NFL comes on late night in the UK when I'm up. I love the colour and energy of it all. There's so many things going on in American football. It took me a while to get it, but I like it a lot.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/blog/music/post/_/id/188/noel-gallagher-talks-solo-tour-man-city|title=Noel Gallagher discusses soccer, solo tour|last=Frye|first=Andy|date=|work=ESPN.com|access-date=2018-03-07}}</ref>\n\nGallagher stated in a 2006 radio interview with Russell Brand that he does not believe in \"God or an all-guiding force\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=63rOA2foEDU |title=Noel Gallagher on Russell Brand Radio Show.avi |publisher=YouTube |date=9 April 2007 |accessdate=9 August 2009}}</ref> Despite this, many of his songs have mentioned God (such as \"[[The Hindu Times]]\" and \"[[Little by Little (Oasis song)|Little by Little]]\"), and all the tracks he had contributed to ''[[Dig Out Your Soul]]'' (as well as the other bandmates' songs) have lyrics and references to God and other biblical terms. ''Dig Out Your Soul'' has been described by Gallagher as a \"religious Armageddon\". In 2009, he stated, \"See, I don't know what I am. If I was an atheist I'd just write songs about not believing in God \u2013 but I don't know what I am.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clashmusic.com/feature/noel-gallagher|title=Noel Gallagher: The Boss|publisher=Clash Music|date=2 October 2008|accessdate=28 June 2009}}</ref> In 2017, he reaffirmed his lack of belief in God in an \"Actually Me\" segment for QC<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2008, Gallagher sold his home in Ibiza near the home of fellow musician [[James Blunt]], saying in an interview that he \"can't stand living there in the knowledge that Blunt is nearby making terrible music\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/nme/34640|title=James Blunt 'forces' Noel Gallagher to move home|date=25 February 2008|work=NME|accessdate=28 June 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080310002011/http://www.nme.com/news/nme/34640|archive-date=10 March 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nGallagher was reportedly asked by [[Simon Cowell]] to be a judge on [[The X Factor (UK)|''The X Factor'']] after [[Dannii Minogue]], [[Cheryl Cole]], and Cowell himself declined to participate in [[The X Factor (UK series 8)|series 8]], but he declined.<ref>{{cite news|title=No forgiveness for Oasis star over X Factor snub|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/showbiz-and-lifestyle/showbiz/2011/08/18/no-forgivemes-for-oasis-star-over-x-factor-snub-91466-29261025/|publisher=Wales Online|date=18 August 2011|accessdate=21 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Gallagher was among the British cultural icons selected by Sir [[Peter Blake (artist)|Peter Blake]] to appear in a new version of his most famous artwork ([[the Beatles]]' ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]'' album cover) to celebrate the British cultural figures of his life.<ref>{{cite news|title=New faces on Sgt Pepper album cover for artist Peter Blake's 80th birthday|url= https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2012/apr/02/peter-blake-sgt-pepper-cover-revisited|agency=The Guardian|date= 11 November 2016}}</ref> \n\nIn August 2017, Gallagher attended Russell Brand's wedding to Laura Gallacher.<ref>{{cite web |title=Russell Brand, 42, marries fiancee Laura Gallacher, 30 |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-4826780/Russell-Brand-42-marries-fiancee-Laura-Gallacher-30.html |website=Mail Online |accessdate=20 November 2019 |date=27 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Songwriting and musicianship==\n===Style and abilities===\nGallagher was the primary songwriter in Oasis, and the sole songwriting contributor on the group's first three albums. He is often criticised for the praise he gives to his own songs, to which he quipped, \"If you'd written '[[Live Forever (Oasis song)|Live Forever]]', you'd be walking to a different tune the next day too.\"<ref>Interview with [[Jonathan Ross (television presenter)|Jonathan Ross]], ''[[Friday Night with Jonathan Ross]]'', 10 September 2004</ref> He has often been accused by critics of plagiarising the music of his heroes, but he has maintained that outright homages in his music are intentional. In a 1996 ''[[Guitar World]]'' interview, he described himself as \"a fan who writes songs\" and stated, \"I'm not saying, 'I'm the greatest songwriter in the world. Listen to me.' Usually, I'm saying, <nowiki>'</nowiki>''These'' are the greatest songwriters in the world. And I'm gonna put them all in this song.'\" His response to critics on the topic of \"blatantly\" stealing riffs was, \"No, I don't feel guilty. But you feel pissed off because you didn't do it first.\"<ref>Caws, Matthew. \"Top of the Pops\". ''Guitar World''. May 1996.</ref> He added, \"When I'm making a record, I've always been of the notion that if a song sounds like [[T. Rex (band)|T. Rex]], well, fuck it, let's make it sound more like T. Rex! I know there's bands that might write something that sounds like [[the Smiths]], and they'll go, 'Oh, it sounds like the Smiths, we've got to make it sound not like the Smiths.' If I'm writing a song and I say to myself, 'Oh, hey, it sounds like [[the Kinks]],' then I'm going to turn it into a Kinks track.\"<ref name=\"bosso\">{{cite web|url=https://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/interview-noel-gallagher-talks-guitars-gear-and-high-flying-birds-512993|title=Interview: Noel Gallagher talks guitars, gear and High Flying Birds|website=[[MusicRadar]]|first=Joe|last=Bosso|date=14 November 2011|accessdate=5 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nGallagher has commented on his musical ability:\n\n{{cquote|I've got a certain style and I've got no control over what I write. I'm not technically proficient enough to attempt all kinds of music. I wish I could write a fucking record like ''[[Raw Power]]'' or ''[[Wish You Were Here (Pink Floyd album)|Wish You Were Here]]'', or have the ability of a musical chameleon. But fuck it, I'm not. I just write these songs because they're real to me and they're coming from a place of truth. And that's it. I don't give a shit about being different. I want to be the same. And that in itself makes me different.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/noel-gallagher-im-not-technically-proficient-enough-to-attempt-all-kinds-of-music-184951/|title=Noel Gallagher: 'I'm Not Technically Proficient Enough to Attempt All Kinds of Music'|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|first=Andy|last=Greene|date=8 August 2011|accessdate=26 October 2019}}</ref>}}\n\nComparing himself to other guitarists, Gallagher stated, \"I can barely play like [[Peter Green (musician)|Peter Green]], let alone fucking [[Jeff Beck]].\"<ref name=\"bosso\"/> He also said, \"I'm unfortunate enough that two of my best mates are [[Johnny Marr]] and [[Paul Weller]]. Those two are [[virtuoso]]s to me although neither of them would admit it. On the electric guitar they're it. So if you're asking me how do I compare to those two\u2014and I like to compare myself to the greats\u2014I'm average at fucking best.\" Weller described Gallagher's ability as a guitarist as \"rudimentary\", saying, \"Noel doesn't pretend to be a guitar god. He's very good at putting chords together and he's got a distinctive style in terms of his chord sequences and his rhythm playing. It's recognisable.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/noel-gallagher-im-average-at-fucking-best-193681|title=Noel Gallagher: \"I'm average at fucking best\"|website=[[MusicRadar]]|first=Michael|last=Leonard|date=27 January 2009|accessdate=27 October 2019}}</ref> Though naturally left-handed, Gallagher plays guitar right-handed, which he claims is the only thing he can do with his non-dominant hand.<ref>Sutcliffe, Phil. \"Meet the New Boss\". ''Mojo Classic: Morrissey and the Story of Manchester''. Vol. 1, issue 13. 2006</ref> \n\nGallagher has said he sometimes does not understand his own lyrics, commenting in 2005, \"When I'm halfway through '[[Don't Look Back in Anger]]' I say to myself, 'I still don't know what these words mean!'\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/new/xmlfeed.nsf/mndwebpages/gallagher%20i%20have%20no%20idea%20what%20my%20songs%20mean|title=GALLAGHER: 'I HAVE NO IDEA WHAT MY SONGS MEAN'|magazine=Contactmusic|date=12 August 2005|accessdate=14 January 2008}}</ref> By 2017, he had reflected, \"There is a bit of truth in that statement. Like the bit in '[[Champagne Supernova]]' about 'slowly walking down the hall faster than a cannonball'. What does that mean? And the answer is, I don't know what it means. I don't care what it means. It must mean something, though, because I play it to a sea of people every night and they seem to understand it. That's all that matters, I guess.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6UYQnpDT1UM|title=Noel Gallagher Goes Undercover on Reddit, YouTube, Twitter and Instagram|date=5 December 2017}}</ref> He has stated that he is [[dyslexia|dyslexic]], which slows down the process of his songwriting, and that he can neither read nor write music.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JNBusPDBQxEC&pg=PA254|title=Off the Record: 25 Years of Music Street Press\n|author1=Sennett, Sean |author2=Groth, Simon |publisher=Univ. of Queensland Press|year=2010|page=254|isbn=978-0-7022-3863-5}}</ref>\n\n===Changing band dynamic===\nGallagher's role as a chief songwriter for Oasis changed over time as he allowed a greater level of lyrical input from the other band members. ''[[Standing on the Shoulder of Giants]]'' included Oasis' first-ever album track written by his brother Liam. ''[[Heathen Chemistry]]'' included a further three tracks by Liam (including \"[[Songbird (Oasis song)|Songbird]]\"), one by [[Gem Archer]], and one by [[Andy Bell (musician)|Andy Bell]]. The album ''[[Don't Believe the Truth]]'' featured another three tracks by Liam (one of them, \"Love Like a Bomb\", co-written with Archer), one from Archer, and two from Bell. The latter two albums have been greeted with increasing critical and commercial success in the UK, particularly ''Don't Believe the Truth''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/search/process?sort=relevance&termType=all&ts=Oasis&ty=2&x=0&y=0|title=Oasis albums reception|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=18 February 2008}}</ref> The second single from ''Don't Believe the Truth'', \"[[The Importance of Being Idle (song)|The Importance of Being Idle]]\", became the second Oasis track sung by Noel to top the UK charts and was named 2005's finest track by [[Q (magazine)|''Q'']] magazine, as well as being nominated for the ''NME''{{'s}} \"Best Song of 2005\" award. On the final Oasis albums, Gallagher's increasing role as lead singer, apparently to compensate for his diminished role as songwriter, caused some tension with Liam.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/archive/2005/05/27/oasis-the-whole-truth-89520-15561438/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080129180642/http://www.mirror.co.uk/archive/2005/05/27/oasis-the-whole-truth-89520-15561438/|title=Oasis: The Whole Truth|last=Manning|first=Toby|work=Daily Mirror |location=UK|date=27 May 2005|accessdate=14 January 2008|archivedate=29 January 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[Zak Starkey]], son of Beatles drummer [[Ringo Starr]] and previous drummer for [[The Who]] and [[Johnny Marr]], replaced long-time drummer [[Alan White (Oasis drummer)|Alan White]] during the recording sessions for ''Don't Believe the Truth''. The loss of White prompted Gallagher to comment in a 2005 interview that he credits Oasis' trouble with drummers, in part, to the fact that he is himself a talented drummer: \"I get a lot of stick for it, but I'm the best drummer in the group.\"<ref name=\"nme2005\">''NME'', issue of 10 December 2005</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nGallagher is well known for his controversial and outspoken statements in the press; he acknowledged his tendency for ''[[faux pa]]s'' in the song \"My Big Mouth\" on the album ''[[Be Here Now (album)|Be Here Now]]''. He has defended himself, saying, \"People think [I'm] controversial for the answers [I] give to silly questions in interviews, but&nbsp;... I'm not thinking about insulting people; I say what I genuinely feel is in my heart. My conscience is clean, d'you know what I mean? Y'know, I'm true to myself\u2014fuck everybody else.\"<ref>Noel Gallagher; Etalk Daily Interview; 2005</ref>\n\n===Damon Albarn and Blur===\nThe most infamous of Gallagher's controversial statements was in a 1995 interview with ''[[The Observer]]'', where he expressed a wish for [[Damon Albarn]] and [[Alex James (musician)|Alex James]] of rivals [[Blur (band)|Blur]] to \"catch [[AIDS]] and die\". He quickly apologised for the comment and stated that \"AIDS is no laughing matter\".<ref name=\"rivalries\">{{cite web | author=Pierce, Ryan | title=Top 10 Music Rivalries: Number 5: Blur vs. Oasis | publisher=AskMen.com | url=http://www.askmen.com/toys/top_10_100/121c_top_10_list.html| accessdate=17 January 2006}}</ref><ref name=\"apology\">{{cite web | author=Titorenko, Mark|date=19 February 1996 | title=Noel's AIDS comment | publisher=The Oasis Archive | url=http://ireland.iol.ie/~kglennon/paper/bandi.htm| accessdate=17 January 2006}} (scroll down to section 3.5)</ref> This statement was preceded by the success of ''(What's the Story) Morning Glory?'', which led to a [[The Battle of Britpop|well-documented feud]] with Blur. The differing styles of the bands, coupled with their prominence within the Britpop movement, led the British media to seize upon the rivalry between the bands. Both groups played along, with the Gallaghers taunting Blur at the 1996 [[BRIT Awards]] by singing a rendition of \"[[Parklife (song)|Parklife]]\" when they collected their \"Best British Band\" award, with Liam changing the lyrics to \"shite-life\".\n\nGallagher maintains that the rivalry was conceived by the magazine ''NME'' and members of Blur's entourage as a ploy to raise their respective profiles, and that he has had no respect for either party ever since. However, Albarn has suggested the roots of the feud were much more personal.<ref>Gallagher and Albarn both interviewed on ''[[Live Forever: The Rise and Fall of Brit Pop]]''; John Dower; 2003</ref> Tension between the two had largely cooled by 2007, and Gallagher said in an ''NME'' interview, \"I've got a lot of respect for Damon, I really do mean it. Because I'm indifferent to Damon he thinks that I think he's a cunt. Our Liam will talk to him, I won't because he's just another singer in a band to me, but I don't think he's a cunt.\"<ref name=\"nme2007\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/oasis/26492|title=Exclusive: Noel Gallagher interview|work=NME|date=17 February 2007|accessdate=14 January 2008}}</ref> On 23 March 2013, Gallagher, Albarn, [[Graham Coxon]], and Paul Weller performed the Blur hit \"[[Tender (song)|Tender]]\" at the [[Teenage Cancer Trust]]. Gallagher and Coxon later provided backing vocals on the song \"We Got the Power\" on Albarn's [[Gorillaz]] album ''[[Humanz]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Luke Morgan Britton |url=http://www.nme.com/news/music/damon-albarn-noel-gallagher-gorillaz-we-got-the-power-2026536 |title=Damon Albarn talks working with Noel Gallagher on new Gorillaz track 'We Got The Power' |publisher=NME |date=23 March 2017 |accessdate=26 July 2017}}</ref> In 2019, he confirmed in an interview with [[Dermot O'Leary]] on [[BBC Two]] that he and Albarn had become friends.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Noel Gallagher|series=Reel Stories|network=[[BBC Two]]|station=[[BBC|British Broadcasting Corporation]]|date=23 June 2019|minutes=9\u201310}}</ref>\n\n===Liam Gallagher===\n[[File:Oasis Noel and Liam WF.jpg|thumb|right|Gallagher (right) performing with [[Liam Gallagher|his brother]] in September 2005]]\nThe Gallagher brothers famously share a turbulent relationship, and one of their arguments was even released on the 1995 [[bootleg recording|bootleg]] single \"[[Wibbling Rivalry]]\". Although their relationship had stabilised in later years, there were a handful of incidents during the band's early career where the two came to blows. At a Los Angeles show during their first American tour in 1994, Liam took to changing the words of the songs so that they were offensive to both Americans and Noel. A confrontation after the show which led to a chair being thrown and a brawl breaking out caused Noel to leave the tour and head for Las Vegas, and he later claimed he had \"visions of ''[[Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas|Fear and Loathing]]'' flashing in [his] eyes\". During recording sessions for ''(What's the Story) Morning Glory?'', the brothers had a violent fight involving a cricket bat when Liam invited everyone from a local pub into the studio while Noel was trying to work.<ref>''Definitely Maybe'' DVD Interview.</ref> In 1995, Noel sang \"[[Wonderwall (song)|Wonderwall]]\" on ''[[Later... with Jools Holland]]'' when Liam failed to turn up.<ref name=Later20111125>{{Cite episode |title=Later&nbsp;... with Jools Holland |episodelink=Later... with Jools Holland |network=BBC Two |airdate=2 December 1995 |series=06 |number=05}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Noel provided lead vocals at a performance for ''[[MTV Unplugged]]'' when Liam backed out minutes before the set was due to start. Liam claimed to have been struck down with a \"sore throat\", but the band later found out that Liam did not like performing acoustically.<ref name=VH1/> Noel was further angered when Liam proceeded to heckle him from the balcony and \"nurse his sore throat\" with beer and cigarettes while the band performed. Just before the band were about to board a plane to the United States for an important make-or-break tour, Liam left the airport, claiming he had to find a house for his then-wife [[Patsy Kensit]]. He later joined the band for their last few gigs and the infamous [[MTV Video Music Awards|MTV Awards]] performance, while the remaining dates were scrapped. The band's future was daily tabloid news.\n\nWhile on tour in [[Barcelona]] in 2000, Oasis were forced to cancel a gig when Alan White's arm seized up, and the band spent the night drinking instead. Liam made a derogatory comment about Gallagher's then-wife [[Meg Mathews]] and attempted to cast doubt over the legitimacy of his daughter Ana\u00efs, causing Noel to headbutt him. Following this, he declared he was quitting overseas touring, but returned for an Oasis gig in [[Dublin]] on 8 July 2000. During the performance, the two brothers shook hands at the end of \"[[Acquiesce]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-5097432.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130828160414/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-5097432.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=28 August 2013|title=Music: The Gallaghers stand on the shoulder of a giant anticlimax|date=16 July 2000|last=Barber|first=Nicholas|work=The Independent |location=UK|accessdate=19 February 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe relationship between the two brothers again became strained throughout 2009, eventually leading to a last-minute cancellation of an Oasis concert scheduled to take place on 28 August in Paris due to an \"altercation within the group\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/oasis/47000 |title=Oasis cancel second festival appearance &#124; News |work=NME |accessdate=3 October 2009}}</ref> Later that evening, Gallagher confirmed he had left Oasis as he \"simply could not go on working with Liam a day longer\". Through the Oasis website, he said, \"It's with some sadness and great relief to tell you that I quit Oasis tonight.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oasisinet.com/NewsArticle.aspx?n=773 |title=Oasis News |publisher=Oasisinet.com |accessdate=3 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090829201005/http://www.oasisinet.com/NewsArticle.aspx?n=773 |archivedate=29 August 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 29 August, he expanded further on his blog: \"The level of verbal and violent intimidation towards me, my family, friends and comrades has become intolerable. And the lack of support and understanding from my management and band mates has left me with no other option than to get me cape and seek pastures new.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/8228687.stm |title=Entertainment &#124; 'Intimidation' behind Oasis split |work=BBC News |date=29 August 2009 |accessdate=23 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nWhen asked in 2012 about his brother and an Oasis reunion, Gallagher said, \"I last texted Liam at Christmas after the [[Manchester City FC|City]] match. I don't think it's gonna happen. It would be great for everyone else except me. It'd be mega for the millions and millions and for everybody else it would be brilliant, but I wouldn't be very happy about it. I guess you don't know what you're gonna feel like in 20-odd years but right now, I mean I was in Oasis for nearly 20 years. I've been doing what I'm doing now for one year and I'd like to see what it's like to do it for longer. I don't think anyone is pushing for a reunion either. Nobody ever brings it up in any seriousness; I mean Liam does publicly but he says a lot of things publicly. I wouldn't take anything he says seriously.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stopcryingyourheartoutnews.blogspot.gr/2012/06/noel-gallagher-on-oasis-reunion.html |title=Noel Gallagher on Oasis Reunion And More ~ Latest Oasis, Beady Eye And Noel Gallagher News |publisher=Stopcryingyourheartoutnews.blogspot.gr |date=27 June 2012 |accessdate=21 November 2012}}</ref> After their performance of \"Wonderwall\" at the London Olympics Closing Ceremony, which Gallagher had originally turned down, he referred to Liam's band [[Beady Eye]] as \"Stratford's finest Oasis tribute band\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Alex Needham |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/aug/15/noel-gallagher-beady-eye |title=Noel Gallagher calls Beady Eye 'Stratford's finest Oasis tribute band'|newspaper=Guardian |accessdate=21 November 2012 |location=London |date=15 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, during an interview with an Australian newspaper, claimed that he and Noel had declared a \"truce\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stopcryingyourheartout.co.uk/2017/12/liam-gallagher-rules-out-oasis-reunion.html|title=Liam Gallagher Rules Out Oasis Reunion Says He And Noel Have Called A Truce}}</ref> However, in February 2018, Liam revealed that the truce did not happen and that it was just \"in his head\" after \"a couple of drinks\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/liam-gallagher-explains-noel-truce-2243541|title=Liam Gallagher explains so-called \"truce\" with Noel|first=Luke Morgan|last=Britton|date=16 February 2018|website=NME}}</ref> In a 2019 interview in Norwegian-Swedish talk show ''[[Skavlan]]'', Noel said that Liam is spreading a false rumour online that Oasis would get back together if Noel's wife would let him, and that she is receiving lots of abuse because of it.<ref>{{cite news |title=Noel Gallagher om Liam: Sprider myt om varf\u00f6r Oasis inte \u00e5terf\u00f6renas |url=https://www.svt.se/kultur/noel-gallagher-om-sin-bror-sprider-myt-om-varfor-oasis-inte-aterforenas |accessdate=5 November 2019 |work=svt.se |date=31 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Jay-Z===\nGallagher reportedly criticised the organisers of the 2008 [[Glastonbury Festival]] for scheduling U.S. [[Hip hop music|hip-hop]] artist [[Jay-Z]] as a headliner for the traditionally rock-focused festival: \"If it ain't broke don't fix it. If you start to break it then people aren't going to go. I'm sorry, but Jay-Z? No chance. Glastonbury has a tradition of guitar music and even when they throw the odd curveball in on a Sunday night you go, '[[Kylie Minogue]]?' I don't know about it. But I'm not having hip-hop at Glastonbury. It's wrong.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7345780.stm|title=Hip-hop \"wrong\" for Glastonbury|work=BBC News |date=12 April 2008|accessdate=7 May 2008|first=Colin|last=Paterson}}</ref> [[Emily Eavis]], the organiser of the festival, said she was honoured Jay-Z was headlining the event: \"He is absolutely the right act for our festival. There is no reason why we should not have the greatest living hip-hop artist on at Glastonbury.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/opinion/commentators/emily-eavis-the-real-reason-we-invited-jayz-to-glastonbury-808985.html|title=Emily Eavis: The real reason we invited Jay-Z to Glastonbury|work=The Independent |location=UK |date=17 April 2008|accessdate=7 May 2008}}</ref> Eavis also reminded Gallagher that [[The Roots]], [[Cypress Hill]], and [[De La Soul]] had all previously performed at Glastonbury. Jay-Z said, \"We don't play guitars, Noel, but hip-hop has put in its work like any other form of music. This headline show is just a natural progression. [...] We have to respect each other's genre of music and move forward.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2008/apr/15/gallagherknowsnothingabout|title=Gallagher knows nothing about Glasto|newspaper=The Guardian|date=15 April 2008|accessdate=6 August 2013|first=Dan|last=Hancox}}</ref>\n\nJay-Z opened his Glastonbury set with a cover of Oasis' song \"Wonderwall\". When Gallagher was asked about the incident, he replied:\n\n{{cquote|The way it's played itself out is that I said Jay-Z had no right to play Glastonbury, which is a crock of horseshit. I got off a plane and someone asked me about the fact that Glastonbury hadn't sold out for the first time in years, and if it was because of Jay-Z. From there it grew into this crap that I was [[Soapbox|standing on an orange crate]] at [[Speakers' Corner]] saying, \"Gather round, brothers and sisters. Have you heard what's happening at Glastonbury this year?\" I have a certain turn of phrase. So if I say, \"Chicken sandwiches in [[McDonald's]] are just plain fucking wrong,\" it doesn't mean I'm attacking all chickens or all sandwiches. I've hung out with Jay-Z in [[Tokyo]]. I've seen his show. It's not my bag, but it's all right. We have a mutual friend in [[Chris Martin]]. [...] I don't dislike rappers or hip-hop or people who like it. I went to the [[Def Jam]] tour in Manchester in the '80s when rap was inspirational. [[Public Enemy (group)|Public Enemy]] were awesome. But it's all about status and bling now, and it doesn't say anything to me.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2008/10/spin-interview-noel-gallagher/?page=0%2C2|title=The SPIN Interview: Noel Gallagher|author=Odell, Michael |work=[[Spin (magazine)|SPIN]]|date=22 September 2008|accessdate=28 June 2009}}</ref>}}\n\nWhen Jay-Z was asked about Gallagher's comments, he said, \"I haven't spoken to [Gallagher], I heard he was reaching out. I don't bear any grudge, it's all good. I just believe in good music and bad music, I've always said that. You look at any interview from the beginning of time, I've always stated that I don't believe in the lines and classifications that people put music in so they can easily define it.\" When asked who he would be interested in collaborating with, he said, \"Anyone. Oasis as well. It doesn't matter to me.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1590390/jayz-hed-be-open-working-with-oasis.jhtml|title=Jay-Z Says He'd Be Open To Working With Noel Gallagher And Oasis: 'I Don't Bear Any Grudge' For Glastonbury Dis|first=Shaheem|last=Reid |work=MTV|date=3 July 2008 |accessdate=28 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Phil Collins===\nGallagher has frequently criticised [[Phil Collins]], saying his music is bland and the opposite of what he stands for. He was quoted as saying, \"People hate fucking cunts like Phil Collins, and if they don't, they fucking should!\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/phil-collins-last-stand-why-the-troubled-pop-star-wants-to-call-it-quits-20110304|title=Phil Collins' Last Stand: Why the Troubled Pop Star Wants to Call It Quits|work=Rolling Stone|date=4 March 2011|accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref> He also called Collins the \"[[antichrist]]\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Lights, camera, sound tracks|p=268|author=Martin Charles Strong, Brendon Griffin|publisher=Canongate|year=2008|isbn=978-1-847-67003-8}}</ref> Prior to the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 UK election]], he stated that he was still supporting the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] government partly because of his concern that \"Phil Collins is threatening to come back and live here [...] and let's face it, none of us want that\".<ref>{{cite news | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/vote_2005/frontpage/4464557.stm | title= Who's backing whom at the election? | work=BBC News | date=21 April 2005 | accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref> Collins responded by saying that Gallagher \"loves slagging me off\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Not Dead Yet: The Autobiography|first=Phil|last=Collins|p=323|publisher=Random House|year=2016|isbn=978-1-473-53614-2}}</ref> He appeared on the BBC television series ''[[Room 101 (British TV series)|Room 101]]'' and nominated to banish the Gallagher brothers, describing them as \"rude and not as talented as they think they are\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Cheers My Arse!: The Funniest Drinking Stories You'll Ever Read|first=Ricky|last=Tomlinson|p=181|publisher=Little Brown Book Group|year=2007|isbn=978-1-847-44168-3}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0078zrb | title= Room 101 | work=BBC Online | accessdate=9 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.genesisfan.net/phil-collins/phil-collins-archive/phil-collins-hits-back-at-noel-gallagher| title=Phil Collins hits back at Noel Gallagher | work=GenesisFan | date=7 September 2005 | accessdate=9 December 2018}}</ref> He also denied that he was a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] supporter in an interview in ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/feb/11/phil-collins-interview-take-a-look-at-me-now-remastered-albums-rerelease-2016 |title= Phil Collins returns: 'I got letters from nurses saying, \"That's it, I'm not buying your records\"' | work=The Guardian |location=London |first=Dorian |last=Lynskey |date=11 February 2016 |access-date=9 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Political views===\nGallagher has spoken about his political views on several occasions. He was quoted: \"Politics is like football for me. [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] is my team and even if you don't like a striker you don't give up supporting the whole team. Labour is the lesser of two evils. What else should we have? Anarchy? Someone has to be responsible.\"<ref>{{cite news | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/2844951.stm | title= Oasis star attacks war protests  | work=BBC News | date=12 March 2003 | accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> In 1997, he visited the recently-appointed [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Tony Blair]] at [[No. 10 Downing Street|10 Downing Street]]. In an interview that year, when he was asked about why he visited Blair, he replied:\n\n{{cquote|I've taken a lot of flack for going to No. 10 Downing Street but the thing about that is, I never considered myself a rebel anyway. I wasn't going there representing the 'Indie community'. I wasn't representing anyone. I was going there for me. You have to understand that from when I went to school and from when I was born all we ever knew was conservative, [[Conservative Party (UK)|Tory]], [[Right wing politics|right-wing]] government. What people don't mention is, they say 'He went to meet Tony Blair.' No. I went to meet the ''Labour'' prime minister. Our parents always drummed into us that the Labour Party was for the people and the Tory Party was not. I went to meet the Labour prime minister.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-Fo76cAojy8 |title=YouTube \u2013 Noel & Liam Gallagher on Radio 1 \u2013 23.10.97 \u2013 Part 3 |publisher=Uk.youtube.com |date=5 October 2008 |accessdate=9 August 2009}}</ref>}}\n\nIn an interview in 2007, when asked about politics, he said:\n\n{{cquote|I'd been unemployed all my life. It was a big deal for me when they (Labour) got in. Now [[David Cameron]] is no different from Tony Blair and [[Gordon Brown]] is no different from David Cameron. They're all cut from the same cloth and it annoys me that the biggest political icon in the last 30 years has been [[Margaret Thatcher]]. Someone who tried to destroy the [[working class]]. It freaks me out. So I don't really think there's anything left to vote for. I believe that I, as a person, can only change things once every 5 years and that's by voting, and my point is that even casting that vote means that the same guy gets in, the only difference is one has a red tie and the other has a blue one.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1hOUN99LtUg |title=YouTube \u2013 Noel on BBC2 NewsNight \u2013 Brit Awards |publisher=Uk.youtube.com |date=14 February 2007 |accessdate=9 August 2009}}</ref>}}\n\nGallagher was passionate in his support for [[Barack Obama]]'s successful bid for US President, calling his acceptance speech to the [[2008 Democratic National Convention]] \"spellbinding.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nme.com/news/nme/39423 |title=Oasis' Noel Gallagher wishes Barack Obama was British &#124; News |work=NME |date=2 September 2008 |accessdate=9 August 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090301184153/http://www.nme.com/news/nme/39423 |archive-date=1 March 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 1997, he played a 5-song set at the Tibetan Freedom Concert in New York City.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uwIQwonJppo |title=YouTube \u2013 7 June 1997 \u2013 Tibetan Freedom Concert in NYC |publisher=Uk.youtube.com |date=24 November 2006 |accessdate=9 August 2009}}</ref> As a result, Oasis were deemed \"unsuitable\" by the Chinese government, forcing a planned tour of the country in 2009 to be cancelled.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7919299.stm |title=Oasis China concerts are shelved |work=BBC News |date=2 March 2009 |accessdate=23 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nGallagher has also been very vocal about [[Knife legislation|knife crime]]. In 2008 he was quoted: \"The scumbags are taking over the streets. I don't know what David Cameron and Gordon Brown are going to do about it. It all goes back to the [[Premiership of Margaret Thatcher|Thatcher years]]. It sounds like a clich\u00e9 but that's when the rot set in.\"<ref>{{cite news | url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/2247270/Noel-Gallagher-blames-Margaret-Thatcher-for-knife-crime.html | title= Noel Gallagher blames Margaret Thatcher for knife crime | work=Daily Telegraph | first=Anita | last=Singh | date=4 July 2008 | accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref> When the interviewer suggested it was for status he replied, \"In my day status was about trying to be somebody, not trying to kill somebody, so how's that all changed?\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-vLwqOeb5ww |title=YouTube \u2013 Noel Gallagher speaks out about knife crime |publisher=Uk.youtube.com |date=4 July 2008 |accessdate=9 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nSpeaking out about the August 2011 riots that took place in England, Gallagher stated, \"Last August I was on tour in Europe and people were asking me about the riots. All over the world, Syria and Egypt, people were rioting for freedom. And these kids in England are rioting for tracksuits. It's embarrassing.\"<ref name=\"digispy1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/celebrity/news/a363982/noel-gallagher-britain-was-better-under-margaret-thatcher.html |title=Noel Gallagher: 'Britain was better under Margaret Thatcher' \u2013 Celebrity News |website=Digital Spy |date=5 February 2012 |accessdate=16 April 2012}}</ref> Gallagher claimed that violent video games and violent television shows which children were being exposed to were partially to blame for social problems.<ref name=\"Riots (causes)\">{{cite journal|title=Noel Gallagher blames 'brutal TV and videogames' for UK riots|journal=[[NME]]|date=14 August 2011|url=http://www.nme.com/news/noel-gallagher/58633|accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, he implied that the UK under the Premiership of Margaret Thatcher was a more fertile ground for dissent in the arts: \"Under Thatcher, who ruled us with an iron rod, great art was made. Amazing designers and musicians. Acid house was born. Very colourful and progressive. Now, no one's got anything to say. 'Write a song? No thanks, I'll say it on Twitter.' It's a sad state when more people retweet than buy records.\"<ref name=\"digispy1\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/noel-gallagher/61846 |title=Noel Gallagher: 'Great music was made in spite of Margaret Thatcher' &#124; News |work=Nme.Com |date=5 February 2012 |accessdate=16 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn a February 2015 interview with ''[[The Quietus]]'', Gallagher elaborated on his disillusion with current politicians and how they'll do anything to say they're just regular people: \"And now the Conservatives are just [...] David Cameron, he's trying to be your mate. 'Oh, I really like [[the Jam]].'\"<ref name = \"the quietus 2015\">{{cite magazine|url = http://thequietus.com/articles/17242-noel-gallagher-high-flying-birds-interview|title = The Apolitical Party: Noel Gallagher Interviewed|magazine=The Quietus|date=16 February 2015}}</ref> Gallagher then went on to say that Thatcher was brutal but more direct, and \"you can kind of respect that\".<ref name = \"the quietus 2015\" />\n\nIn an interview with [[HuffPost]] shortly before the [[2015 United Kingdom general election]], he summed up his views of contemporary political leaders: \"David Cameron a bell-end, Ed Miliband a [[Communism|communist]], the rest of them don't really count\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2015/05/01/noel-gallagher-david-cameron-bellend-huffpost-live_n_7192704.html |title=Noel Gallagher Calls Prime Minister 'David Cameron A Bell-End, Ed Miliband A Communist' On HuffPost Live (VIDEO) |last=Frost |first=Caroline |date=1 May 2015 |website=[[HuffPost]] |access-date=28 November 2018}}</ref> In 2016, Gallagher stated that while he remained [[Left-wing politics|left-wing]], he opposed Milliband's replacement as Labour leader, [[Jeremy Corbyn]], deeming him to be another communist. He said that \"the Tories don't care about the vulnerable, and the communists don't care about the aspirational.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hendicott|first1=James|title=Noel Gallagher hits out at Jeremy Corbyn: 'I don't like communism'|url=http://www.nme.com/news/noel-gallagher/90690|accessdate=10 January 2016|publisher=NME|date=10 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nGallagher did not vote in the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 EU referendum]], saying that he \"didn\u2019t think we should have been given the vote in the first place because as ordinary members of the public how are the fuck are you qualified to talk about the break-up of the oldest continent in the fucking world.\" However, he also said that he felt Britain should have remained part of the EU saying, \"I feel right at the time of it happening, we turned our back on the French, who were going through some dark terror shit.\" Conversely, he also said, \"But it\u2019s happened now. It was a legal vote. Fucking get it done and let\u2019s move on.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/noel-gallagher-brexit-remainers-get-over-liam-oasis-a8058766.html|title=Noel Gallagher's explicit Brexit rant is quite something|date=2017-11-16|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-02-19}}</ref>\n\n==Musical equipment==\n[[File:Noel Gallagher live in Rome 2012.JPG|thumb|Noel Gallagher playing a [[C. F. Martin & Company|Martin]] acoustic guitar in Rome on 13 March 2012]]\nThroughout his career, Gallagher has used a wide range of different guitars, effect pedals and amplifiers from his large collection. Most of it emerged from the ''Standing on the Shoulder of Giants'' sessions, where he decided to drop the equipment used in the three previous albums and instead buy \"loads of really weird pedals, old guitars, and small amps,\" as the lack of deadline to deliver the album allowed Gallagher to \"take quite a few days just messing around.\"<ref name=guitarone>{{cite journal|url=http://www.clarkamplification.com/gtronemagazine.html|title=Interview with Noel Gallagher|journal=[[Guitar World|Guitar One]]|publisher=[[Harris Publications]]|date=October 2002|accessdate=17 August 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Guitars===\n;Electric guitars\n* [[Epiphone Les Paul]]<ref name=guitarone/> \u2013 Gallagher played a cherry sunburst model in the early years of Oasis.\n* [[Gibson Les Paul]]<ref name=guitarone/> \u2013 A sunburst Les Paul was given to Gallagher by [[Johnny Marr]], formerly of [[the Smiths]], in the early days of Oasis. When this Les Paul was destroyed, Marr gave him another Les Paul, used prominently on the Smiths' album ''[[The Queen Is Dead|The Queen is Dead]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/whats-on/johnny-marr-loaned-noel-gallagher-7793976|title=Johnny Marr loaned Noel Gallagher two guitars in early days of Oasis - and never got either back|last=Heward|first=Emily|date=2014-09-18|website=men|access-date=2019-02-03}}</ref>\n* [[Fender Telecaster]] \u2013 Gallagher uses several, one of which, a '60s model, was given to Noel by [[Johnny Depp]] as a birthday present.<ref name=guitarone/>\n* [[Epiphone Casino]]<ref name=guitarone/>\n* [[Gibson ES-355]] Vintage Model<ref name=guitarone/> \u2013 Since 2001, this has become Gallagher's main stage guitar.\n\n===Effect pedals===\nIn the early days of Oasis, Gallagher did not use pedals: \"I used to just turn up the amps as full as I could get them.\"<ref name=guitarone/> Since then, he has begun using a large number of effects, but singled out the [[Ibanez Tube Screamer]].<ref name=guitarone/>\n\n===Amplification===\nGallagher has said that he used only 100-watt [[Marshall Amplification|Marshalls]] early in his career. After ''Definitely Maybe'', he began using smaller amps, singling out [[Fender Amplifiers|Fenders]] ([[Fender Princeton|Princeton]] and [[Fender Bandmaster|Bandmaster]]), and also a combo made by Clark Amplification, which builds amplifiers based on vintage Fender and Marshall amps.<ref name=guitarone/>\n\n==Discography==\n{{See also|Oasis discography|Noel Gallagher's High Flying Birds discography}}\n\n===Noel Gallagher's High Flying Birds===\n====Albums====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:210px;\"|Album details\n!colspan=\"9\"|Peak chart positions\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Certifications\n|-\n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:75%\"|UK<br /><ref>{{cite web|title=Archive Chart|url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/3/2011-10-29//|work=[[UK Albums Chart]]|publisher=[[The Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=23 October 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219230351/http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/3/2011-10-29/|archivedate=19 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:75%\"|FRA<br /><ref name=\"fra\">{{cite web|url=http://lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Noel+Gallagher%27s+High+Flying+Birds&titel=Noel+Gallagher%27s+High+Flying+Birds&cat=a|title=French Charts > Oasis|language=French |publisher=lescharts.com Hung Medien|accessdate=2 September 2008}}</ref>\n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:75%\"|GER<br /><ref name=\"geralb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.de/album.asp?artist=Noel+Gallagher%27s+High+Flying+Birds&title=Noel+Gallagher%27s+High+Flying+Birds&cat=a&country=de|title=Album \u2013 Noel Gallagher's High Flying Birds,''Noel Gallagher's High Flying Birds''|language=German|publisher=[[Media Control Charts]]|accessdate=17 March 2011}}</ref>\n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:75%\"|IRE<br /><ref>{{cite web|title=Noel Gallagher's High Flying Birds \u2013 Noel Gallagher's High Flying Birds \u2013 Irish Charts// |url=http://irma.ie/aucharts.asp |work=[[Irish Albums Chart]] |publisher=[[Irish Recorded Music Association]] |accessdate=23 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511020134/http://irma.ie/aucharts.asp |archivedate=11 May 2012 }}</ref>\n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:75%\"|ITA<br /><ref name=\"fra\"/>\n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:75%\"|JPN<br /><ref name=\"jpn\" >{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/search/result.php?kbn=ja&types=rnk&year=2011&month=10&week=4&submit5.x=23&submit5.y=18|title=Japanese Album Charts: Week 4,&nbsp;October 2011|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Oricon]]|accessdate=13 December 2011|quote=5 \u30ce\u30a8\u30eb\u30fb\u30ae\u30e3\u30e9\u30ac\u30fc\u30ba\u30fb\u30cf\u30a4\u30fb\u30d5\u30e9\u30a4\u30f3\u30b0\u30fb\u30d0\u30fc\u30ba\uff08\u521d\u56de\u751f\u7523\u9650\u5b9a\u76e4\uff09 \u30ce\u30a8\u30eb\u30fb\u30ae\u30e3\u30e9\u30ac\u30fc\u30ba\u30fb\u30cf\u30a4\u30fb\u30d5\u30e9\u30a4\u30f3\u30b0\u30fb\u30d0\u30fc\u30ba 10/12 22777 }}</ref>\n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:75%\"|KOR<br /><ref name=\"kor\">{{cite web|title=Gaon Album Charts|url=http://www.gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/album/list.gaon|work=[[Gaon Chart]]. Week from 2011.10.30 \u2013 2011.11.05|language=Korean|accessdate=23 October 2011}}</ref>\n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:75%\"|SPA<br /><ref name=\"fra\"/>\n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:75%\"|US<br /><ref name=\"allmusicalbums\">{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r2302250|tab=charts-awards|label=Charts and awards for ''Noel Gallagher's High Flying Birds''}}</ref>\n|-\n|2011\n|align=\"left\"|'''''[[Noel Gallagher's High Flying Birds (album)|Noel Gallagher's High Flying Birds]]'''''\n*Released: 16 October 2011\n*Label: Sour Mash\n*Formats: [[LP record|LP]], [[Compact disc|CD]], CD+[[DVD]], [[Music download|digital download]]\n| 1\n| 9\n| 11\n| 1\n| 2\n| 5\n| 12\n| 15\n| 28\n|align=\"left\"|\n*UK: 2x Platinum<ref name=\"bpi\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx |title=BPI: Certified Awards Search |publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]] (BPI) |accessdate=29 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090924015932/http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/Search.aspx |archivedate=24 September 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n|2015\n|align=\"left\"|'''''[[Chasing Yesterday (album)|Chasing Yesterday]]'''''\n*Released: 2 March 2015\n*Label: Sour Mash\n*Formats: LP, CD, Digital download\n| 1\n| 15\n| 5\n| 1\n| 5\n| 10\n| 12\n| 19\n| 35\n|align=\"left\"|\n*UK: Platinum\n|-\n|2017\n|align=\"left\"|'''''[[Who Built the Moon?]]'''''\n* Released: 24 November 2017\n* Label: Sour Mash\n* Formats: LP, CD, digital download\n|1\n|44\n|17\n|2\n|12\n|7\n|\n|\n|48\n|\n* UK: Gold\n|}\n\n====Singles====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Single\n! colspan=\"2\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"|[[UK Singles Chart|UK]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"|[[Irish Singles Chart|IRE]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2011\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"[[The Death of You and Me]]\"\n| 15\n| 35\n| rowspan=\"5\"|''