ft;\"|\"[[The Death of You and Me]]\"\n| 15\n| 35\n| rowspan=\"5\"|''[[Noel Gallagher's High Flying Birds (album)|Noel Gallagher's High Flying Birds]]''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"[[AKA... What a Life!]]\"\n| 20\n| \u2013\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"[[If I Had a Gun...]]\"\n| 95\n| \u2013\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2012\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"[[Dream On (Noel Gallagher song)|Dream On]]\"\n| 52\n| \u2013\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"[[Everybody's on the Run]]\"\n| 61\n| \u2013\n|-\n||2014\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"[[In the Heat of the Moment]]\"\n| 26\n| 71\n| rowspan=\"5\"|''[[Chasing Yesterday (album)|Chasing Yesterday]]''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"|2015\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"[[Ballad of the Mighty I]]\"\n| 75\n| \u2013\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"[[Riverman]]\"\n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| \"[[Lock All the Doors]]\"\n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| \"The Dying Of the Light\"\n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2017\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"[[Holy Mountain (song)|Holy Mountain]]\"\n| 31\n| \u2013\n| rowspan=\"4\"|''[[Who Built the Moon?]]''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;|\"[[It's a Beautiful World]]\"\n| 77\n| \u2013\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2018\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"[[She Taught Me How to Fly]]\"\n| 71\n| \u2013\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"[[If Love Is the Law]]\"\n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Live Albums ===\n* ''[[The Dreams We Have as Children \u2013 Live at the Royal Albert Hall]]'' (2009)\n\n'''Also featured on:'''\n* 1995: ''[[Stanley Road]]'' by [[Paul Weller]], acoustic guitar on \"I Walk on Gilded Splinters\"\n* 1997: ''[[Dig Your Own Hole]]'' by [[the Chemical Brothers]], vocals on \"[[Setting Sun (The Chemical Brothers song)|Setting Sun]]\"\n* 1998: ''[[Saturnz Return]]'' by [[Goldie]], guitar on \"Temper Temper\"\n* 1998: ''[[The X-Files: The Album]]'', the track \"Teotihuacan\"\n* 1998: ''[[More Than Us|More Than Us E.P.]]'' by [[Travis (band)|Travis]], the track \"All I Want To Do Is Rock (Live Version)\"\n* 1999: ''[[Surrender (The Chemical Brothers album)|Surrender]]'' by [[the Chemical Brothers]], vocals on \"[[Let Forever Be]]\"\n* 2000: ''Tailgunner'' by [[Mark Coyle|Tailgunner]], drums\n* 2001: ''[[The Same Old Blues]]'' by [[Proud Mary (band)|Proud Mary]], production, plus additional vocals, guitars, bass and percussion\n* 2002: ''[[Illumination (Paul Weller album)|Illumination]]'' by Paul Weller, drums, percussion & bass on \"One X One\"\n* 2003: ''Polaris'' by [[North Mississippi Allstars]], vocals on \"One To Grow On\" & \"Polaris\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/72141/gallagher-guests-on-new-mississippi-allstars-set|title=Gallagher Guests On New Mississippi Allstars Set|website=Billboard}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/polaris-mw0000023794/credits|title=Polaris - North Mississippi Allstars &#124; Credits|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n* 2003: ''[[Live at the Royal Albert Hall (The Who album)|Live at the Royal Albert Hall]]'' by [[the Who]], guitar, backing vocals on \"[[Won't Get Fooled Again]]\"\n* 2004: ''Always Outnumbered, Never Outgunned'' by the Prodigy, bass on \"Shoot Down\"\n* 2004: ''[[Solarized]]'' by [[Ian Brown]]: collaboration on the song \"[[Keep What Ya Got]]\".\n* 2004: ''[[All Years Leaving]]'' by [[the Stands]], guitar on \"Some Weekend Night\"\n* 2008: ''[[22 Dreams]]'' by [[Paul Weller]], bass, piano, mellotron and Wurlitzer on \"Echoes Round the Sun\"\n* 2011: ''[[Colour of the Trap]]'' by [[Miles Kane]], backing vocals on \"My Fantasy\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Miles Kane reveals new Noel Gallagher album collaborations|url=http://www.nme.com/news/miles-kane/53970|work=NME|date=24 November 2010}}</ref>\n* 2015: ''[[A Head Full Of Dreams]]'' by [[Coldplay]], guitar on \"[[Up&Up]]\"\n* 2017: ''[[Humanz]]'' by [[Gorillaz]], backing vocals on \"We Got the Power\"\n* 2018: ''[[True Meanings]]'' by Paul Weller, pump organ\n* 2020: ''[[Walls (Louis Tomlinson album)|Walls]]'' by [[Louis Tomlinson]], writing credits on \"[[Walls (Louis Tomlinson song)|Walls]]\"\n\n===Other charted songs===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Single\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"|[[UK Singles Chart|UK]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\"|2009\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"[[Don't Look Back in Anger]]\"<br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(Live for Teenage Cancer Trust)</span>\n| 101\n| rowspan=\"5\"|''[[The Dreams We Have as Children \u2013 Live at the Royal Albert Hall|The Dreams We<br/>Have as Children<br/>- Live at the Royal<br/>Albert Hall]]''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"[[Talk Tonight]]\"<br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(Live for Teenage Cancer Trust)</span>\n| 119\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"Cast No Shadow\"<br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(Live for Teenage Cancer Trust)</span>\n| 120\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"[[Whatever (Oasis song)|(It's Good) To Be Free]]\"<br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(Live for Teenage Cancer Trust)</span>\n| 121\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"[[The Importance of Being Idle (song)|The Importance of Being Idle]]\"<br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(Live for Teenage Cancer Trust)</span>\n| 141\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\"|2011\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"The Good Rebel\"<br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">([[Noel Gallagher's High Flying Birds (band)|Noel Gallagher's High Flying Birds]] \u2013 B-Side)</span>\n| 192\n| \"[[The Death of You and Me]]\"\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"Let the Lord Shine a Light on Me\"<br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">([[Noel Gallagher's High Flying Birds (band)|Noel Gallagher's High Flying Birds]] \u2013 B-Side)</span>\n| 107\n| \"[[AKA... What a Life!]]\"\n|}\n\n===As featured artist===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Single\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"|[[UK Singles Chart|UK]]\n|-\n| 1995\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"Come Together\"<br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(The Smokin' Mojo Filters)</span>\n| 19\n| ''[[The Help Album]]''\n|-\n| 1996\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"[[Setting Sun (The Chemical Brothers song)|Setting Sun]]\"<br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">([[The Chemical Brothers]] featuring Noel Gallagher)</span>\n| 1\n| ''[[Dig Your Own Hole]]''\n|-\n| 1998\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"Temper Temper\"<br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">([[Goldie]] featuring Noel Gallagher)</span>\n| 13\n| ''[[Saturnz Return]]''\n|-\n| 1998\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"[[Let Forever Be]]\"<br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(The Chemical Brothers featuring Noel Gallagher)</span>\n| 9\n| ''[[Surrender (The Chemical Brothers album)|Surrender]]''\n|-\n| 1998\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"[[More Than Us|All I Want To Do Is Rock]]\" (Live Version)<br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(Travis featuring Noel Gallagher)</span>\n| 16\n| ''[[More Than Us|More Than Us E.P.]]''\n|-\n| 2004\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"Keep What Ya Got\"<br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">([[Ian Brown]] featuring Noel Gallagher)</span>\n| 18\n| ''[[Solarized]]''\n|-\n| 2017\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"[[We Got the Power (Gorillaz song)|We Got the Power]]\"<br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">([[Gorillaz]] featuring [[Savages (band)|Jehnny Beth]], [[DRAM (rapper)|DRAM]] & Noel Gallagher)</span>\n| \u2013\n| ''[[Humanz]]''\n|}\n\n===Other===\n*2004: \"Free Love, Freeway\" \u2013 Ricky Gervais ft. Noel Gallagher; credited as  'a special guest' on backing vocals for the 'Office Christmas Special DVD', on which the video of the recording session featuring Noel & Ricky is available\n*2011: ''Well&nbsp;... All Right!'' \u2013 compilation album compiled by Gallagher, released [[covermount]] into ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'' magazine\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin|colwidth=30em}}\n* Gallagher, Paul; Christian, Terry. ''Brothers, From Childhood to Oasis'' (Virgin Books)\n* Harris, John. ''Britpop!: Cool Britannia and the Spectacular Demise of English Rock''. Da Capo Press, 2004. {{ISBN|0-306-81367-X}}\n* Hewitt, Paolo. ''Getting High: The Adventures of Oasis'' (Boxtree Press)\n* Mathur, Paul. ''Take Me There: The Story of Oasis'' (Bloomsbury Publishing PLC)\n* Middles, Mick. ''Oasis: Round Their Way'' (Independent Music Press)\n* Moody, P. ''Oasis: Lost Inside'' (UFO Music Ltd)\n* Robertson, I. ''Oasis: What's The Story?'' (Blake Books)\n* Wheeler, J. ''Oasis: How Does It Feel?'' (UFO Books Ltd)\n* Hingley, Tom. ''Carpet Burns \u2013 My life with Inspiral Carpets'' (Route) {{ISBN|978-1-901927-54-2}}\n* Williams, J. & Cook J. ''Oasis member attacked on stage'' (Canoe.ca)\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{official website|http://www.noelgallagher.com/}}\n* {{IMDb name|0302462}}\n\n{{Noel Gallagher's High Flying Birds}}\n{{Oasis}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gallagher, Noel}}\n[[Category:Noel Gallagher]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Alternative rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:Britpop musicians]]\n[[Category:English male singers]]\n[[Category:English people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:English rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:English singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Ivor Novello Award winners]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) people]]\n[[Category:Lead guitarists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Manchester]]\n[[Category:NME Awards winners]]\n[[Category:Oasis (band) members]]\n[[Category:People with dyslexia]]\n[[Category:People from Burnage]]\n[[Category:People from Longsight]]\n[[Category:Road crew]]\n[[Category:English male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Noel Gallagher's High Flying Birds members]]\n", "name_user": "Leohodgson111111", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noel_Gallagher"}
{"title_page": "Howard A. Rodman", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Howard A. Rodman\n\n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = \n|occupation = screenwriter<br> author <br> educator\n| known_for   =  ''[[Savage Grace]]''<br> ''[[August (2008 film)|August]]''<br>''[[Joe Gould's Secret (film)]]''<br>''Destiny Express''<br>''The Great Eastern''\n}}\n'''Howard A. Rodman''' is a  [[screenwriter]], [[author]] and [[educator]]. He is the former President of the [[Writers Guild of America, West]], professor and former chair of the writing division at the [[USC School of Cinematic Arts]],<ref>{{Cite web|title=USC School of Cinematic Arts Directory Profile|url=http://cinema.usc.edu/faculty/profile.cfm?id=6619&first=&last=&title=&did=19&referer=facultydirectory.cfm&startpage=1&startrow=31}}</ref> and an artistic director of the [[Sundance Institute]] Screenwriting Labs.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Sundance Institute|url=http://history.sundance.org/people/24164}}</ref> He is the son of screenwriter Howard Rodman (1920\u20131985).\n\n==Career==\nIn his 20s and early 30s Rodman was a typist, a legal proofreader, a mail-room clerk, a union organizer (for the Committee of Interns and Residents) and the guitarist for various lower-Manhattan post-punk bands (Made in USA, Arsenal, Soul Sharks).<ref>http://cinema.usc.edu/faculty/profile.cfm?id=6619</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/howard-a-rodman | work=Huffington Post | title=Howard A. Rodman}}</ref> Starting as editor-in-chief of ''[[The Cornell Daily Sun]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|title=The Cornell Daily Sun|url=http://cornellsun.com/node/16695|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130120030158/http://cornellsun.com/node/16695|archivedate=2013-01-20}}</ref> Rodman has published scores of articles in venues including ''The New York Times'',<ref>{{Cite news|title=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/05/27/archives/jaywalking-with-a-twotime-loser.html | first=Howard A. | last=Rodman|date=May 27, 1971}}</ref> ''The Los Angeles Times'',<ref>{{Cite news|title=The Los Angeles Times|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/la-oe-rodman17oct17,0,1677290.story | first=Howard A. | last=Rodman|date=October 17, 2007}}</ref> ''Los Angeles Magazine'',<ref>{{Cite web|title=Los Angeles Magazine|url=http://www.lamag.com/features/author/howard-a-rodman|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222031456/http://www.lamag.com/features/author/howard-a-rodman|archivedate=2014-02-22}}</ref> and the ''Village Voice'' (for which he was a monthly columnist).<ref>{{Cite news|title=Variety|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117866448?refCatId=14}}</ref>\n\n'Destiny Express', an historical romance set in the pre-war German film community, was published in January 1990 by [[Atheneum Books]]. <ref>https://isbnsearch.org/isbn/9780689120909</ref>\n\nHis adaptations of Jim Thompson, David Goodis et al. for Showtime's ''[[Fallen Angels (American TV series)|Fallen Angels]]'' anthology series<ref>{{Cite web|title=Fallen Angels|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0105994/fullcredits#cast}}</ref> were directed by [[Steven Soderbergh]] and [[Tom Cruise]]. Rodman then wrote ''[[Joe Gould's Secret (film)|Joe Gould's Secret]]'', which opened the 2000 Sundance festival and was subsequently released by October/USA Films. Rodman's original screenplay ''F.'' was selected by ''Premiere Magazine'' as one of Hollywood's Ten Best Unproduced Screenplays.<ref>{{Cite web|title=BAFTA Events Archive|url=http://www.baftala.org/screenings/archive/index.php?page=17&type=event&year=}}</ref> Other films include ''[[Savage Grace]]'', starring Julianne Moore, and ''[[August (2008 film)|August]]'', with Josh Hartnett, Rip Torn, and David Bowie\u2014both of which had their US premieres at the [[List of films at the 2008 Sundance Film Festival|2008 Sundance Film Festival]]. They were released in 2008 from IFC and First Look, respectively. Rodman's screenplay for ''Savage Grace'' was nominated for a Spirit Award in the Best Screenplay category.\n\n== ''The Great Eastern'' ==\n\nThe novel ''[[The Great Eastern (Rodman novel)|The Great Eastern]]'' by Howard A. Rodman was published<ref>https://www.mhpbooks.com/books/the-great-eastern/</ref> on June 4, 2019, by [[Melville House Publishing]]. \n\nIt is a sprawling adventure set in the 1850s-1870s in New York, London, Paris, India, and the North Atlantic. The story pits two of literature's most iconic anti-heroes against each other: [[Captain Nemo]] and [[Captain Ahab]]. Caught between them is real-life British engineer [[Isambard Kingdom Brunel]], builder of the century's greatest ship, {{SS|Great Eastern}}. Brunel is kidnapped by Nemo to help design a submarine with which to fight the laying of the [[transatlantic telegraph cable]], which links the two colonialist forces Nemo hates, England and the US. Brunel finds himself going up against his own ship, and the strange man hired to protect it, Captain Ahab.\n\nIn March 2019, the film rights to ''The Great Eastern'' were acquired by the UK film company Great Point Media, and Rodman was commissioned to write the screen adaptation.<ref>{{Cite magazine |title=Howard A. Rodman\u2019s Book \u2018The Great Eastern\u2019 to Be Adapted Into Movie|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/howard-a-rodman-great-eastern-movie-1203163719/ |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n\n== Reviews ==\n*{{cite news| url=https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/past-and-pastiche-in-howard-a-rodmans-the-great-eastern/| title=Past and Pastiche in Howard A. Rodman\u2019s \u201cThe Great Eastern\u201d| author=[[Brian Evenson]]| date=July 15, 2019| work=Los Angeles Review of Books}}\n*{{cite news| url=https://nbmagazine.co.uk/the-great-eastern-by-howard-a-rodman/| title= \"The Great Eastern\" by Howard A. Rodman| author=[[Paul Burke]]{{dn|date=February 2020}}| date=June 15, 2019 || work=NB Magazine}}\n*{{cite news| url=http://thetangential.com/2019/07/17/book-review-howard-rodmans-the-great-eastern-pits-ahab-against-nemo/| title= Howard Rodman\u2019s \u201cThe Great Eastern\u201d Pits Ahab Against Nemo| author=[[Jay Gabler]]| date=July 17, 2019| work=The Tangential}}\n\n== Other activities ==\nHe founded and chairs the Writers Guild Independent Writers Caucus.<ref>{{Cite web|title=WGAW The Independent Writers Caucus (IWC)|url=http://www.wga.org/subpage_writersresources.aspx?id=925|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006045406/http://wga.org/subpage_writersresources.aspx?id=925|archivedate=2012-10-06}}</ref> He has chaired FilmIndependent's Spirit Awards feature film jury<ref>{{Cite web|title=Movieweb|url=http://www.movieweb.com/news/2007-film-independents-spirit-awards-nominations-announced}}</ref> as well as the USC Scripter Awards.<ref>{{Cite web|title=25th Annual USC Libraries Scripter Award|url=http://www.usc.edu/libraries/scripter/}}</ref> He is a Fellow of the Los Angeles Institute for the Humanities;<ref>{{Cite web|title=LAIH Fellows, Howard A. Rodman|url=http://www.usc.edu/libraries/partners/laih/fellows/HowardA.Rodman.htm}}</ref> a member of the executive committee of the writers' branch of the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences;<ref>{{Cite web|title=Academy Invites 134 to Membership|url=http://www.oscars.org/press/pressreleases/2009/20090630.html}}</ref> a former trustee of the Writers Guild Foundation;<ref>{{Cite web|title=Writers Guild Foundation Staff & Board|url=https://www.wgfoundation.org/about-us-writers-community/staff-and-board/}}</ref> vice-chair of the Committee on the Professional Status of Writers;<ref>{{Cite news|title=The Hollywood Reporter, WGAW 2011 Elections|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/howard-a-rodman-228632 | first=Jonathan | last=Handel|date=August 28, 2011}}</ref> and serves on several nonprofit boards, among them the Franco-American Cultural Fund,<ref>{{Cite web|title=16th Annual City of Lights City of Angels Film Festival|url=http://www.zimbio.com/photos/Howard+A.+Rodman/16th+Annual+City+Lights+City+Angels+Film+Festival/VuLk3f7K9Yv}}</ref> and Cornell in Hollywood.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Cornell Alumni Magazine|url=http://cornellalumnimagazine.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=485&Itemid=56&ed=12}}</ref> He is an alumnus of the Seed Fund Board of the [[Liberty Hill Foundation]],<ref>{{Cite web|title=Liberty Hill Foundation|url=http://www.libertyhill.org/page.aspx?pid=586}}</ref> and a former editor of ''The Bill of Rights Journal''.<ref>{{Cite web|title=The Bill of Rights Journal N.E.C.L.C. 25th Anniversary December 1976|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B002DTA1P0}}</ref>\n\nHoward is also on Los Angeles committee of PEN America<ref>https://pen.org/los-angeles-committee/</ref>. [[PEN International]] stands at the intersection of literature and human rights to protect free expression in the United States and worldwide.<ref>https://pen.org/about-us/</ref>\n\nHe is a member of the National Film Preservation Board, which advises Librarian of Congress on the annual selection of films to the National Film Registry. It also advises on national film preservation planning policy.<ref>https://www.loc.gov/static/programs/national-film-preservation-board/documents/NFPB_Members_1988-2019.pdf</ref>\n\nWorking with the Library Foundation of Los Angeles<ref>https://lfla.org/event/dictionaries-and-the-bending-of-language/</ref>, USC<ref>https://cinema.usc.edu/faculty/profile.cfm?id=6619&first=&last=&title=&did=50&referer=%2Ffaculty%2Ffacultydirectory.cfm&startpage=1&startrow=181</ref>, and the Writers Guild<ref>https://www.wga.org/the-guild/about-us/history/presidents</ref>, Rodman has conducted public conversations with such writers as Tom Wolfe<ref>https://www.lapl.org/collections-resources/e-media/podcasts/aloud/evening-tom-wolfe</ref>, Ricky Jay, Jeannette Seaver, Vince Gilligan, Geoff Dyer, and Lady Antonia Fraser.<ref>https://www.lapl.org/collections-resources/e-media/podcasts/aloud/must-you-go-my-life-harold-pinter</ref><ref>https://cinema.usc.edu/faculty/profile.cfm?id=6619&first=&last=&title=&did=50&referer=%2Ffaculty%2Ffacultydirectory.cfm&startpage=1&startrow=181</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, he was a member of the jury<ref>https://www.festivalcannes1939.com/the-jury</ref> at the Cannes 1939 Film Festival in Orl\u00e9ans France.<ref>https://www.festivalcannes1939.com/1st-cannes-film-festival-1939</ref>\n\nHoward Rodman also contributes to the [[Los Angeles Review of Books]]<ref>https://lareviewofbooks.org/contributor/howard-a-rodman</ref>. His latest articles include '[http://After%20Hours%20Capitalism:%20On%20Tom%20Lutz\u2019s%20\u201cBorn%20Slippy After Hours Capitalism: On Tom Lutz\u2019s \u201cBorn Slippy]\u201d'<ref>https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/after-hours-capitalism-on-tom-lutzs-born-slippy/</ref> a review of [[Tom Lutz]]\u2019s \u201cBorn Slippy\u201d<ref>https://repeaterbooks.com/product/born-slippy-a-novel/</ref>, published by [[Repeater Books]] and [https://blog.lareviewofbooks.org/essays/192nd-anniversary-birth-jules-verne/ 'On the 192nd Anniversary of the Birth of Jules Verne'.]\n\n==Honors and awards==\nOn October 31, 2013, Rodman was named a Chevalier de [[l'Ordre des Arts et des Lettres]] by the French Republic.<ref>http://www.deadline.com/2013/10/global-showbiz-briefs-broadchurch-book-the-escape-artist-sales-bassem-youssef-louis-delluc-shortlist-more/</ref>\n\nIn February 2018 he was inducted into [[Final Draft (software)]]'s Screenwriters Hall of Fame,<ref>{{Cite news|title=Final Draft Awards to Honor 'The Post's' Liz Hannah and Former WGA West Chief Howard Rodman|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/race/final-draft-awards-posts-liz-hannah-wga-west-president-howard-rodman-be-honored-10776684 | work=Hollywood Reporter | first=Scoott|last=Feinberg|date=January 23, 2018}}</ref> alongside [[Robert Towne]], [[Steven Zaillian]], [[Aaron Sorkin]], [[Nancy Meyers]], [[Paul Schrader]], [[Lawrence Kasdan]] et al.\n\n==Personal life==\nHe was married to the writer and media scholar [[Anne Friedberg]],<ref>{{Cite news|title=Anne Friedberg dies at 57; professor at USC's School of Cinematic Arts|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/oct/14/local/me-anne-friedberg14 | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Elaine|last=Woo|date=October 14, 2009}}</ref> author of ''The Virtual Window''.<ref>{{Cite web|title=The MIT Press: The Virtual Window|url=http://mitpress.mit.edu/catalog/item/default.asp?tid=10780&ttype=2|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120921044639/http://mitpress.mit.edu/catalog/item/default.asp?ttype=2&tid=10780|archivedate=2012-09-21}}</ref> until her death in 2009; they have one son, Tristan Rodman. Their house, the 1957 [[John Lautner]] \"Zahn Residence,\" has been widely published. Their work with Lautner in restoring it was chronicled in the February 2002 issue of ''Dwell'' magazine.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Dwell|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MsQDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA50&lpg=PA50&dq=zahn+dwell+rodman&source=bl&ots=HnogF41Ebw&sig=W9AeIlF5vQ3roYrt7yz9K-Q56s4&hl=en&sa=X&ei=2_xyUNb-KsHviQKKuYDABA&ved=0CCAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=zahn%20dwell%20rodman&f=false}}</ref>  In June 2017 he wed the artist and professor Mary Beth Heffernan.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0734912}}\n* [http://cinema.usc.edu/faculty/profile.cfm?id=6619&first=&last=&title=&did=19&referer=facultydirectory.cfm&startpage=1&startrow=31 Howard Rodman's USC faculty page]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rodman, Howard A.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American instructional writers]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from California]]\n[[Category:American male novelists]]\n[[Category:American television writers]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:University of Southern California faculty]]\n[[Category:Chevaliers of the Ordre des Arts et des Lettres]]\n[[Category:Screenwriting instructors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:Novelists from California]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Howard A. Rodman\n\n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = \n|occupation = screenwriter<br> author <br> educator\n| known_for   =  ''[[Savage Grace]]''<br> ''[[August (2008 film)|August]]''<br>''[[Joe Gould's Secret (film)]]''<br>''Destiny Express''<br>''The Great Eastern''\n}}\n'''Howard A. Rodman''' is a  [[screenwriter]], [[author]] and [[educator]]. He is the former President of the [[Writers Guild of America, West]], professor and former chair of the writing division at the [[USC School of Cinematic Arts]],<ref>{{Cite web|title=USC School of Cinematic Arts Directory Profile|url=http://cinema.usc.edu/faculty/profile.cfm?id=6619&first=&last=&title=&did=19&referer=facultydirectory.cfm&startpage=1&startrow=31}}</ref> and an artistic director of the [[Sundance Institute]] Screenwriting Labs.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Sundance Institute|url=http://history.sundance.org/people/24164}}</ref> He is the son of screenwriter Howard Rodman (1920\u20131985).\n\n==Career==\nIn his 20s and early 30s Rodman was a typist, a legal proofreader, a mail-room clerk, a union organizer (for the Committee of Interns and Residents) and the guitarist for various lower-Manhattan post-punk bands (Made in USA, Arsenal, Soul Sharks).<ref>http://cinema.usc.edu/faculty/profile.cfm?id=6619</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/howard-a-rodman | work=Huffington Post | title=Howard A. Rodman}}</ref> Starting as editor-in-chief of ''[[The Cornell Daily Sun]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|title=The Cornell Daily Sun|url=http://cornellsun.com/node/16695|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130120030158/http://cornellsun.com/node/16695|archivedate=2013-01-20}}</ref> Rodman has published scores of articles in venues including ''The New York Times'',<ref>{{Cite news|title=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/05/27/archives/jaywalking-with-a-twotime-loser.html | first=Howard A. | last=Rodman|date=May 27, 1971}}</ref> ''The Los Angeles Times'',<ref>{{Cite news|title=The Los Angeles Times|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/la-oe-rodman17oct17,0,1677290.story | first=Howard A. | last=Rodman|date=October 17, 2007}}</ref> ''Los Angeles Magazine'',<ref>{{Cite web|title=Los Angeles Magazine|url=http://www.lamag.com/features/author/howard-a-rodman|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222031456/http://www.lamag.com/features/author/howard-a-rodman|archivedate=2014-02-22}}</ref> and the ''Village Voice'' (for which he was a monthly columnist).<ref>{{Cite news|title=Variety|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117866448?refCatId=14}}</ref>\n\n'Destiny Express', an historical romance set in the pre-war German film community, was published in January 1990 by [[Atheneum Books]]. <ref>https://isbnsearch.org/isbn/9780689120909</ref>\n\nHis adaptations of Jim Thompson, David Goodis et al. for Showtime's ''[[Fallen Angels (American TV series)|Fallen Angels]]'' anthology series<ref>{{Cite web|title=Fallen Angels|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0105994/fullcredits#cast}}</ref> were directed by [[Steven Soderbergh]] and [[Tom Cruise]]. Rodman then wrote ''[[Joe Gould's Secret (film)|Joe Gould's Secret]]'', which opened the 2000 Sundance festival and was subsequently released by October/USA Films. Rodman's original screenplay ''F.'' was selected by ''Premiere Magazine'' as one of Hollywood's Ten Best Unproduced Screenplays.<ref>{{Cite web|title=BAFTA Events Archive|url=http://www.baftala.org/screenings/archive/index.php?page=17&type=event&year=}}</ref> Other films include ''[[Savage Grace]]'', starring Julianne Moore, and ''[[August (2008 film)|August]]'', with Josh Hartnett, Rip Torn, and David Bowie\u2014both of which had their US premieres at the [[List of films at the 2008 Sundance Film Festival|2008 Sundance Film Festival]]. They were released in 2008 from IFC and First Look, respectively. Rodman's screenplay for ''Savage Grace'' was nominated for a Spirit Award in the Best Screenplay category.\n\n== ''The Great Eastern'' ==\n\nThe novel ''[[The Great Eastern (Rodman novel)|The Great Eastern]]'' by Howard A. Rodman was published<ref>https://www.mhpbooks.com/books/the-great-eastern/</ref> on June 4, 2019, by [[Melville House Publishing]]. \n\nIt is a sprawling adventure set in the 1850s-1870s in New York, London, Paris, India, and the North Atlantic. The story pits two of literature's most iconic anti-heroes against each other: [[Captain Nemo]] and [[Captain Ahab]]. Caught between them is real-life British engineer [[Isambard Kingdom Brunel]], builder of the century's greatest ship, {{SS|Great Eastern}}. Brunel is kidnapped by Nemo to help design a submarine with which to fight the laying of the [[Transatlantic telegraph cable]], which links the two colonialist forces Nemo hates, England and the US. Brunel finds himself going up against his own ship, and the strange man hired to protect it, Captain Ahab.\n\nIn March 2019, the film rights to ''The Great Eastern'' were acquired by the UK film company Great Point Media, and Rodman was commissioned to write the screen adaptation.<ref>{{Cite magazine |title=Howard A. Rodman\u2019s Book \u2018The Great Eastern\u2019 to Be Adapted Into Movie|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/howard-a-rodman-great-eastern-movie-1203163719/ |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n\n== Reviews ==\n*{{cite news| url=https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/past-and-pastiche-in-howard-a-rodmans-the-great-eastern/| title=Past and Pastiche in Howard A. Rodman\u2019s \u201cThe Great Eastern\u201d| author=[[Brian Evenson]]| date=July 15, 2019| work=Los Angeles Review of Books}}\n*{{cite news| url=https://nbmagazine.co.uk/the-great-eastern-by-howard-a-rodman/| title= \"The Great Eastern\" by Howard A. Rodman| author=[[Paul Burke]]{{dn|date=February 2020}}| date=June 15, 2019 || work=NB Magazine}}\n*{{cite news| url=http://thetangential.com/2019/07/17/book-review-howard-rodmans-the-great-eastern-pits-ahab-against-nemo/| title= Howard Rodman\u2019s \u201cThe Great Eastern\u201d Pits Ahab Against Nemo| author=[[Jay Gabler]]| date=July 17, 2019| work=The Tangential}}\n\n== Other activities ==\nHe founded and chairs the Writers Guild Independent Writers Caucus.<ref>{{Cite web|title=WGAW The Independent Writers Caucus (IWC)|url=http://www.wga.org/subpage_writersresources.aspx?id=925|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006045406/http://wga.org/subpage_writersresources.aspx?id=925|archivedate=2012-10-06}}</ref> He has chaired FilmIndependent's Spirit Awards feature film jury<ref>{{Cite web|title=Movieweb|url=http://www.movieweb.com/news/2007-film-independents-spirit-awards-nominations-announced}}</ref> as well as the USC Scripter Awards.<ref>{{Cite web|title=25th Annual USC Libraries Scripter Award|url=http://www.usc.edu/libraries/scripter/}}</ref> He is a Fellow of the Los Angeles Institute for the Humanities;<ref>{{Cite web|title=LAIH Fellows, Howard A. Rodman|url=http://www.usc.edu/libraries/partners/laih/fellows/HowardA.Rodman.htm}}</ref> a member of the executive committee of the writers' branch of the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences;<ref>{{Cite web|title=Academy Invites 134 to Membership|url=http://www.oscars.org/press/pressreleases/2009/20090630.html}}</ref> a former trustee of the Writers Guild Foundation;<ref>{{Cite web|title=Writers Guild Foundation Staff & Board|url=https://www.wgfoundation.org/about-us-writers-community/staff-and-board/}}</ref> vice-chair of the Committee on the Professional Status of Writers;<ref>{{Cite news|title=The Hollywood Reporter, WGAW 2011 Elections|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/howard-a-rodman-228632 | first=Jonathan | last=Handel|date=August 28, 2011}}</ref> and serves on several nonprofit boards, among them the Franco-American Cultural Fund,<ref>{{Cite web|title=16th Annual City of Lights City of Angels Film Festival|url=http://www.zimbio.com/photos/Howard+A.+Rodman/16th+Annual+City+Lights+City+Angels+Film+Festival/VuLk3f7K9Yv}}</ref> and Cornell in Hollywood.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Cornell Alumni Magazine|url=http://cornellalumnimagazine.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=485&Itemid=56&ed=12}}</ref> He is an alumnus of the Seed Fund Board of the [[Liberty Hill Foundation]],<ref>{{Cite web|title=Liberty Hill Foundation|url=http://www.libertyhill.org/page.aspx?pid=586}}</ref> and a former editor of ''The Bill of Rights Journal''.<ref>{{Cite web|title=The Bill of Rights Journal N.E.C.L.C. 25th Anniversary December 1976|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B002DTA1P0}}</ref>\n\nHoward is also on Los Angeles committee of PEN America<ref>https://pen.org/los-angeles-committee/</ref>. [[PEN International]] stands at the intersection of literature and human rights to protect free expression in the United States and worldwide.<ref>https://pen.org/about-us/</ref>\n\nHe is a member of the National Film Preservation Board, which advises Librarian of Congress on the annual selection of films to the National Film Registry. It also advises on national film preservation planning policy.<ref>https://www.loc.gov/static/programs/national-film-preservation-board/documents/NFPB_Members_1988-2019.pdf</ref>\n\nWorking with the Library Foundation of Los Angeles<ref>https://lfla.org/event/dictionaries-and-the-bending-of-language/</ref>, USC<ref>https://cinema.usc.edu/faculty/profile.cfm?id=6619&first=&last=&title=&did=50&referer=%2Ffaculty%2Ffacultydirectory.cfm&startpage=1&startrow=181</ref>, and the Writers Guild<ref>https://www.wga.org/the-guild/about-us/history/presidents</ref>, Rodman has conducted public conversations with such writers as Tom Wolfe<ref>https://www.lapl.org/collections-resources/e-media/podcasts/aloud/evening-tom-wolfe</ref>, Ricky Jay, Jeannette Seaver, Vince Gilligan, Geoff Dyer, and Lady Antonia Fraser.<ref>https://www.lapl.org/collections-resources/e-media/podcasts/aloud/must-you-go-my-life-harold-pinter</ref><ref>https://cinema.usc.edu/faculty/profile.cfm?id=6619&first=&last=&title=&did=50&referer=%2Ffaculty%2Ffacultydirectory.cfm&startpage=1&startrow=181</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, he was a member of the jury<ref>https://www.festivalcannes1939.com/the-jury</ref> at the Cannes 1939 Film Festival in Orl\u00e9ans France.<ref>https://www.festivalcannes1939.com/1st-cannes-film-festival-1939</ref>\n\nHoward Rodman also contributes to the [[Los Angeles Review of Books]]<ref>https://lareviewofbooks.org/contributor/howard-a-rodman</ref>. His latest articles include '[http://After%20Hours%20Capitalism:%20On%20Tom%20Lutz\u2019s%20\u201cBorn%20Slippy After Hours Capitalism: On Tom Lutz\u2019s \u201cBorn Slippy]\u201d'<ref>https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/after-hours-capitalism-on-tom-lutzs-born-slippy/</ref> a review of [[Tom Lutz]]\u2019s \u201cBorn Slippy\u201d<ref>https://repeaterbooks.com/product/born-slippy-a-novel/</ref>, published by [[Repeater Books]] and [https://blog.lareviewofbooks.org/essays/192nd-anniversary-birth-jules-verne/ 'On the 192nd Anniversary of the Birth of Jules Verne'.]\n\n==Honors and awards==\nOn October 31, 2013, Rodman was named a Chevalier de [[l'Ordre des Arts et des Lettres]] by the French Republic.<ref>http://www.deadline.com/2013/10/global-showbiz-briefs-broadchurch-book-the-escape-artist-sales-bassem-youssef-louis-delluc-shortlist-more/</ref>\n\nIn February 2018 he was inducted into [[Final Draft (software)]]'s Screenwriters Hall of Fame,<ref>{{Cite news|title=Final Draft Awards to Honor 'The Post's' Liz Hannah and Former WGA West Chief Howard Rodman|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/race/final-draft-awards-posts-liz-hannah-wga-west-president-howard-rodman-be-honored-10776684 | work=Hollywood Reporter | first=Scoott|last=Feinberg|date=January 23, 2018}}</ref> alongside [[Robert Towne]], [[Steven Zaillian]], [[Aaron Sorkin]], [[Nancy Meyers]], [[Paul Schrader]], [[Lawrence Kasdan]] et al.\n\n==Personal life==\nHe was married to the writer and media scholar [[Anne Friedberg]],<ref>{{Cite news|title=Anne Friedberg dies at 57; professor at USC's School of Cinematic Arts|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/oct/14/local/me-anne-friedberg14 | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Elaine|last=Woo|date=October 14, 2009}}</ref> author of ''The Virtual Window''.<ref>{{Cite web|title=The MIT Press: The Virtual Window|url=http://mitpress.mit.edu/catalog/item/default.asp?tid=10780&ttype=2|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120921044639/http://mitpress.mit.edu/catalog/item/default.asp?ttype=2&tid=10780|archivedate=2012-09-21}}</ref> until her death in 2009; they have one son, Tristan Rodman. Their house, the 1957 [[John Lautner]] \"Zahn Residence,\" has been widely published. Their work with Lautner in restoring it was chronicled in the February 2002 issue of ''Dwell'' magazine.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Dwell|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MsQDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA50&lpg=PA50&dq=zahn+dwell+rodman&source=bl&ots=HnogF41Ebw&sig=W9AeIlF5vQ3roYrt7yz9K-Q56s4&hl=en&sa=X&ei=2_xyUNb-KsHviQKKuYDABA&ved=0CCAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=zahn%20dwell%20rodman&f=false}}</ref>  In June 2017 he wed the artist and professor Mary Beth Heffernan.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0734912}}\n* [http://cinema.usc.edu/faculty/profile.cfm?id=6619&first=&last=&title=&did=19&referer=facultydirectory.cfm&startpage=1&startrow=31 Howard Rodman's USC faculty page]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rodman, Howard A.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American instructional writers]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from California]]\n[[Category:American male novelists]]\n[[Category:American television writers]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:University of Southern California faculty]]\n[[Category:Chevaliers of the Ordre des Arts et des Lettres]]\n[[Category:Screenwriting instructors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:Novelists from California]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Clarityfiend", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eThe Great Eastern:lowercase", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Howard_A._Rodman"}
